(2, 2, 'a:42:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:13:"<p>ECP-02</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:399:"<p>The purpose is to ensure that Protected Health Information (PHI) transmitted outside of PIPL to other organizations under contract with PIPL is protected and limited to that information needed for providing clinical and administrative services. This policy is intended to act as a guide to transmitting data efficiently while maintaining confidentiality of Protected Health Information (PHI).</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:186:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, and temporary workers.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:1534:"<p>PIPL provides protection on the use and disclosure of PHI transmitted to entities outside of the organization as set forth by the HIPAA Privacy Rule. This includes electronic transmission of health information to external vendors or entities. Individual circumstances dictate the need for specific policies. Refer to the following PIPL policies and procedures for additional information:</p><ol><li>PRIVACY: ECP-03: Minimum Necessary Policy summary: &ldquo;Employees may not use, request, or disclose to others, any PHI that is more than the minimum necessary to accomplish the purpose of the use, request, or disclosure. This includes business information.&rdquo;</li><li>PRIVACY: ECP-06: Use and Disclosure of PHI as Permitted or Required by a Business Associate Agreement (BAA) summary: &ldquo;PIPL and its personnel may use and disclose PHI as permitted or required by a Business Associate Agreement (BAA), and when Client authorization is required to do so.&rdquo;</li><li>SECURITY: ECP-228: Business Associate Agreement and Other Arrangements Policy summary: &ldquo;PHI may be disclosed to a business associate if there is a written agreement with the business associate.&rdquo;</li><li>PRIVACY: ECP-09: Use and Disclosure of PHI Requiring Client Authorization Policy summary: &ldquo;This policy sets forth the circumstances in which PIPL and its personnel must obtain valid Client authorization for a use and disclosure of the Client&rsquo;s PHI. This policy sets the requirements for a valid authorization.&rdquo;</li></ol>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_8";s:254:"<p>All individuals identified in the scope of this policy are responsible for meeting the requirements of this policy.<br />The PIPL Privacy Officer is responsible for maintaining this policy and communicating this policy to members of the workforce.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:9:"Retention";s:5:"des_9";s:336:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention. Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_10";s:262:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other privacy policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as the HIPAA Privacy Rule and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_11";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_12";s:1783:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>HIPAA Final Privacy Rule, 45 CFR Part 164.514(h), Department of Health and Human Services, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/</a> August 14, 2002.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_13";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_14";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";}', '', '', 0),
(3, 3, 'a:42:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:13:"<p>ECP-04</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:225:"<p>This policy establishes the general rule regarding the minimum necessary limitation on the Use or Disclosure of Protected Health Information (PHI) as set forth by the HIPAA Privacy Rule (45 CFR 164.502(b), 164.514(d)).</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:186:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, and temporary workers.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:2737:"<ol><li>Employees may not use, request, or disclose to others, any PHI that is more than the minimum necessary to accomplish the purpose of the use, request, or disclosure. This includes business information.</li><li>PIPL shall limit disclosures to the extent practicable to the limited data set, as defined in 45 CFR section 164.514(e)(2), or if needed by the receiving entity, to the minimum necessary to accomplish the intended purpose of the use, Disclosure, or request.</li><li>Employees who use PHI not related to their jobs (orally, or from written records or computer terminals) or employees who disclose PHI to any party, which is in violation of this policy or any other privacy policy, shall be subject to disciplinary procedures as per the PIPL &nbsp;Sanction Policy including, but not limited to, dismissal.&nbsp; All employees are required to sign and abide by the Employee Confidentiality and Security Agreement. See Security Policy ECP-214, Security Awareness and Training Policy.</li><li>PIPL may rely on a request from another entity for PHI as representing the minimum necessary for the stated purpose, if such reliance is reasonable under the circumstances, and if:<ul><li>The request is from a public official</li><li>The disclosure to the public official must otherwise be permitted under PIPL&rsquo;s policies</li><li>The public official must represent that the information requested is the minimum necessary for the stated purpose(s)</li><li>The information is requested by another covered entity</li><li>The information is requested by a professional who is an employee or is a business associate</li><li>The purpose of the request is to provide professional services to the covered entity, and</li><li>The professional represents that the information requested is the minimum necessary for the stated purpose(s)</li></ul></li></ol><p><strong>Exceptions:&nbsp; </strong></p><ol><li>PIPL is not limited in the amount of PHI that it may disclose to a provider of health care for the purpose of medical treatment.&nbsp;</li><li>When federal or state law requires a disclosure of PHI, the minimum necessary information is that which is required to comply with such law.&nbsp; Requests for PHI made by the federal government in the course of a complaint investigation or compliance review and undertaken under Federal Privacy Rule are deemed to meet the minimum necessary rule.</li><li>The minimum necessary rule does not apply when disclosing a Client&rsquo;s PHI to themselves or to the Client&rsquo;s personal representative.</li><li>All information that is requested within an authorization may be disclosed in accordance with that authorization.&nbsp; This policy does not limit such disclosures.&nbsp;</li></ol>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_8";s:254:"<p>All individuals identified in the scope of this policy are responsible for meeting the requirements of this policy.<br />The PIPL Privacy Officer is responsible for maintaining this policy and communicating this policy to members of the workforce.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:9:"Retention";s:5:"des_9";s:336:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention. Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_10";s:262:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other privacy policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as the HIPAA Privacy Rule and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_11";s:54:"<p>Employee Confidentiality and Security Agreement</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_12";s:1792:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>HIPAA Final Privacy Rule, 45 CFR Part 164.514(h), Department of Health and Human Services, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/</a> August 14, 2002.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a><ul></ul></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_13";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_14";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";}', '', '', 0),
(4, 4, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:13:"<p>ECP-05</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:347:"<p>This policy establishes guidelines to help safeguard Protected Health Information (PHI) from being seen, heard or disclosed to those who are not authorized to see or hear it as set forth by the HIPAA Privacy Rule (45 CFR 164.530(c)), a Covered Entities&rsquo; Business Associate Agreement, &nbsp;as well as other policies developed by PIPL.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:186:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, and temporary workers.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:4194:"<p>PIPL employees must reasonably safeguard PHI to limit incidental uses or disclosures.&nbsp; An incidental use or disclosure is a secondary use or disclosure that cannot reasonably be prevented, is limited in nature, and occurs as a result of an otherwise permitted use or disclosure.&nbsp; For example: a conversation that is overheard despite attempts by the speakers to avoid being heard.</p><p>All employees must follow these guidelines in handling PHI:</p><p><strong>Guidelines to Safeguard PHI:</strong></p><p><strong>Paper documents contained within PIPL offices:</strong></p><ol><li>In self-contained work areas that are locked after business hours, documents containing PHI must not be in plain sight.</li><li>Management will take reasonable steps to provide work areas, which are not self-contained and locked, with lockable file cabinets or storage bins, lockable desk drawers, or other means to secure PHI during periods when the area is left unattended.</li></ol><p><strong>Workstation access and use:</strong></p><ol><li>Refer to PIPL&rsquo;s Security policies on workstation use and workstation security.</li></ol><p><strong>Copying documents that contain PHI:</strong></p><ol><li>When copying documents that contain PHI for purposes of disclosing to an external party, copy only the information that is necessary to accomplish the task. This may require part of a page to be masked.</li></ol><p><strong>Disposal of paper documents that contain PHI:</strong></p><ol><li>Paper documents that contain PHI must be disposed of in one of the locked Security Containers located throughout the building. Documents placed in the locked Security Containers will be shredded by a contracted vendor. Paper documents containing PHI must never be thrown away in regular trashcans or insecure recycle bins.</li></ol><p><strong>Home office:</strong></p><ol><li>PIPL employees may not take documents that contain PHI out of the facility unless authorized to do so by management.</li><li>Employees authorized to work from a home office must assure that the home office complies with all applicable policies and procedures regarding the security and privacy of PHI, including these guidelines.</li><li>Do not store any electronic files that contain PHI on the home computer&rsquo;s hard drive (c: drive). Electronic files that contain PHI should only be stored on network drives that can only be accessed by an ID and password.</li></ol><p><strong>Transporting documents that contain PHI outside of PIPL offices:</strong></p><ol><li>Employees who work from home must transport documents that contain PHI in a locked container. Management is responsible to provide locked containers to employees who work from home.</li><li>Employees who occasionally transport documents that contain PHI outside of PIPL offices (i.e. from one building to another or to a home office), must take reasonable steps to secure the documents. For example: If possible, documents should be in a locked container. Documents must be in some type of folder, bag, or container where PHI is not visible. Documents must never be left in an unlocked unattended vehicle.</li></ol><p><strong>Smartphones and Tablets (i.e. BlackBerrys, iPhones, Droids, iPads):</strong></p><ol><li>PIPL privacy and security policies apply to PHI stored on smartphones and tablets.</li><li>Users of smartphones and tablets are responsible for assuring that the PHI on their devices is kept secure and private. This includes password protecting the device and locking the device when not in use.</li><li>Loss or theft of a device must be reported to the Information Security Officer or Privacy Officer immediately.</li></ol><p><strong>Printers:</strong></p><ol><li>Printers must be located in secure areas, where only employees can access documents.</li><li>Employees must pick up printed documents that contain PHI from the printers by the end of each day. Exception: home analysts may print batch summary sheets to the Operations printer after hours.</li></ol><p><strong>Building Security:</strong></p><ol><li>Refer to the building security policies and procedures for PIPL policy on employee, visitor and vendor access to the building.</li></ol>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_8";s:255:"<p>All individuals identified in the scope of this policy are responsible for meeting the requirements of this policy.</p><p>The PIPL Privacy Officer is responsible for maintaining this policy and communicating this policy to members of the workforce.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:9:"Retention";s:5:"des_9";s:336:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention. Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_10";s:262:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other privacy policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as the HIPAA Privacy Rule and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_11";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_12";s:1783:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>HIPAA Final Privacy Rule, 45 CFR Part 164.514(h), Department of Health and Human Services, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/</a> August 14, 2002.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_13";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_14";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:0:"";s:6:"des_15";s:0:"";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(5, 5, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:13:"<p>ECP-08</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:235:"<p>The Covered Entity has the right to request an accounting of disclosures of their Clients Protected Health Information (PHI) as set forth by the HIPAA Privacy Rule (45 CFR 164.528) and the HITECH ACT, if requested by the Client.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:186:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, and temporary workers.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:2870:"<ol><li>A Client has the right to receive an accounting of disclosures of PHI made by PIPL in the six (6) years prior to the date on which the accounting is requested.</li><li>The following are disclosures, which PIPL is required to track on the Client&rsquo;s record:<ul><li>When required by law or for law enforcement purposes.</li><li>When requested by a government authority regarding information about victims of abuse, neglect or domestic violence.</li><li>Health oversight activities.</li><li>Judicial and administrative proceedings (ex: court orders, subpoenas, discovery requests).</li><li>To comply with workers&rsquo; compensation investigations.</li><li>To avert a serious threat to health or safety.</li></ul></li><li>For multiple disclosures to the same recipient for a single purpose, a summary of accounting addressing the series of disclosures is acceptable, rather than detailing an account of each disclosure.</li><li>PIPL is also required to track all accidental disclosures. Some examples of common accidental disclosures are:<ul><li>PHI faxed to wrong location.</li><li>Document containing PHI mailed to wrong person (i.e. EOB, letter).</li><li>Paid wrong provider (claims remit containing PHI sent to wrong provider).</li></ul></li><li>The Client must request, in writing to the Covered Entity,&nbsp; the accounting of disclosures, ; specifying the time period to which the accounting applies, which may not be for a period of more than six (6) years, and be reviewed and approved by the Privacy Officer.</li><li>The Covered Entity must then notify PIPL of this request.</li><li>PIPL must provide the accounting to the Covered Entity, in writing, within 30 days of the date the request for the accounting was received. The contents of the accounting should include the following:<ul><li>The date of the disclosure.</li><li>The name of the entity or persons who received the PHI and if known, the addresses of such persons.</li><li>A brief description of the PHI disclosed.</li><li>A brief statement of the purposes of the disclosure.</li><li>Any relevant documentation, such as a written request from a government or law enforcement agency.</li></ul></li><li>PIPL is not required to track the following disclosures:<ul><li>For national security or intelligence purposes.</li><li>To correctional institutions or law enforcement officials having lawful custody of an inmate.</li><li>Incidental disclosures permitted under applicable federal or state law. <em>For purposes of this policy an incidental disclosure is a secondary disclosure that cannot reasonably be prevented and that occurs as a result of an otherwise permitted use or disclosure. Example: a conversation that is overheard despite attempts by the speakers to avoid being heard.</em></li><li>Disclosures that occurred prior to the compliance date (April 14, 2003).</li></ul></li></ol>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:9:"Procedure";s:5:"des_8";s:1945:"<p><strong>RECORDING DISCLOSURES</strong></p><p>Authorized Employee</p><ol><li>Discloses PHI that PIPL is required to document or is made aware of an accidental disclosure that has been made.</li><li>Complete the form for recording Accounting of Disclosures.</li><li>Attach the supporting documentation to the form.</li><li>Forward completed form and supporting documentation to the Privacy Officer.</li></ol><p>Privacy Officer</p><ol><li>Receives completed form for Accounting of Disclosures and supporting documentation.</li><li>Reviews for appropriate Accounting of Disclosure.</li><li>Records the disclosure in Customer Center.</li></ol><p><strong>ACCOUNTING OF DISCLOSURE REQUEST FROM THE CLIENT</strong></p><p>Authorized Employee</p><ol><li>Receives a request from a Client&rsquo;s Personal Representative for Accounting of disclosures.</li><li>Sends the Accounting of Disclosures form to the Client or Client&rsquo;s Personal Representative to complete, sign and return to the Privacy Officer.</li></ol><p>Privacy Officer</p><ol><li>Receives a completed Accounting of Disclosures form from a Client.</li><li>Reviews the request to determine which disclosures are reportable.</li><li>Records the request in Customer Center.</li><li>If the request for an accounting of disclosures is granted:<ol><li>Works with the appropriate staff to obtain documents of the specified information.</li><li>Sends documents to the Client within 30 days.</li></ol></li><li>If the request cannot be granted within 30 days, sends letter to the Client. The letter must state the reason for the delay and the date on which the accounting will be provided to the Client.</li><li>If the request for an accounting of disclosures is denied based on the exceptions in the policy section, send a denial letter.</li><li>Documents the denial or the accounting in Customer Center.</li><li>Files a copy of the written accounting and request in the privacy files.</li></ol>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:254:"<p>All individuals identified in the scope of this policy are responsible for meeting the requirements of this policy.<br />The PIPL Privacy Officer is responsible for maintaining this policy and communicating this policy to members of the workforce.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:336:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention. Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:262:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other privacy policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as the HIPAA Privacy Rule and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:1783:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>HIPAA Final Privacy Rule, 45 CFR Part 164.514(h), Department of Health and Human Services, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/</a> August 14, 2002.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(6, 6, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:13:"<p>ECP-09</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:421:"<p>There are a number of situations in which members of the PIPL workforce may disclose Protected Health Information (PHI). Disclosures of PHI must be made in accordance with the applicable PIPL&rsquo;s policies. In each case, the member of the workforce making the disclosure must verify the individual requesting the information is authorized to receive it as set forth by the HIPAA Privacy Act (45 CFR 164.514(h)).</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:186:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, and temporary workers.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:262:"<p>This policy sets forth the circumstances in which PIPL and its personnel must obtain valid Client authorization for a use and disclosure of the Client&rsquo;s Protected Health Information (PHI). This policy sets the requirements for a valid authorization.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:9:"Procedure";s:5:"des_8";s:5268:"<ol><li>PIPL personnel will obtain Client authorization to use or disclose the Client&rsquo;s PHI in the following circumstances:<ul><li>When PIPL policy does not expressly allow disclosure of the PHI without Client authorization.</li><li>The disclosure is for certain mental health records.&nbsp;</li><li>The disclosure is of communicable disease information&mdash;including HIV or AIDS-related information.</li><li>The disclosure is for marketing purposes.&nbsp;</li><li>Sale of protected health information</li></ul></li><li>If Client authorization is required for disclosure of Client PHI, PIPL personnel must obtain Client authorization on the PIPL Release of Information Form (Attachment A) that contains the following items:<ul><li>A specific and meaningful description of the PHI to be used or disclosed;</li><li>The name of the person, class of persons, or organization making the disclosure of PHI, <em>e.g.</em>, PIPL;</li><li>The name or other identification of the person, class of persons, or organization to whom PIPL is making the disclosure (or PIPL, if the disclosure is for an internal purpose);</li><li>A description of the purpose of the use or disclosure of PHI.&nbsp; If the Client has requested the disclosure, indicate &ldquo;at the request of the Client.&rdquo;</li><li>An expiration date or an expiration event of the authorization that relates to the purpose of the use or disclosure;</li><li>A statement that PIPL cannot condition treatment on whether the Client signs the authorization.&nbsp; (However, if PIPL is allowed to condition treatment on obtaining authorization, as explained in paragraph 6 below, the authorization form must include a statement of the consequences to the Client for refusing to sign the authorization);</li><li>The potential that the Client&rsquo;s PHI may be re-disclosed by the recipient and no longer be protected by the Federal Privacy regulations;</li><li>The Client&rsquo;s (or Personal Representative&rsquo;s) signature and the date of signature; and</li><li>If the authorization is executed by a Personal Representative, a description of that person&rsquo;s authority to act for the Client, and</li><li>If the authorization is for the purpose of using PHI for marketing and PIPL will receive either direct or indirect payment, tell the Client in the authorization form.</li></ul></li><li>If PIPL receives an authorization form from a source outside PIPL, PIPL personnel will ensure that the outside authorization form meets the requirements set forth in paragraph 2 above.</li><li>PIPL personnel may not combine authorizations for different purposes.&nbsp; The only exception is that, if the authorization is for use and disclosure of PHI for treatment involved in a research study, personnel may combine the informed consent to participate in the study with the authorization to use and disclose the PHI for that study.</li><li>PIPL personnel will not require a Client to provide an authorization, and will not condition treatment on obtaining authorization, except in the following circumstances:<ul><li>The Client is participating in research, and the authorization is sought in connection with that research.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li></ul></li><li>PIPL personnel will not use or disclose PHI if the Client&rsquo;s authorization is invalid.&nbsp; An authorization is invalid if:<ul><li>The authorization has expired because the expiration date has passed or the expiration event has passed;</li><li>The authorization form lacks a required element or has not been filled out completely;</li><li>PIPL is aware that the Client has revoked the authorization;</li><li>PIPL knows that the form contains false information, or</li><li>The authorization is combined with another authorization&mdash;except for research purposes.</li></ul></li><li>If they become aware of information that would render a Client&rsquo;s authorization invalid, PIPL personnel will report that information to the Compliance Office.&nbsp; This includes information that a Client has revoked his or her authorization, has expressed the desire to revoke his or her authorization, or that an authorization form contains false information.</li><li>A Client may revoke his or her authorization at any time by submitting a written request to PIPL personnel.&nbsp; PIPL personnel who receive a Client&rsquo;s verbal request to revoke an authorization will refer the Client to the Compliance Office.&nbsp; PIPL personnel who receive a Client&rsquo;s written revocation of authorization will send a copy of the revocation to Health Information Management and a copy to the Compliance Office.</li><li>Upon revocation of Client authorization, PIPL personnel will stop using or disclosing Client&rsquo;s PHI for the purposes covered by that authorization.&nbsp; However, if there is an important reason to continue to use or disclose that PHI (for example, the Client&rsquo;s PHI must be used for quality assurance purposes), PIPL personnel should contact the Compliance Office for further guidance.</li><li>PIPL personnel will give the Client a copy of the authorization signed by the Client.</li><li>PIPL will retain copies of all Client authorizations for six (6) years.&nbsp; All Client authorizations will be kept in the medical record.</li></ol>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:254:"<p>All individuals identified in the scope of this policy are responsible for meeting the requirements of this policy.<br />The PIPL Privacy Officer is responsible for maintaining this policy and communicating this policy to members of the workforce.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:336:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention. Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:263:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as the HIPAA Privacy Rule and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:49:"<p>Release of Information Form (Attachment A)</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:1782:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>HIPAA Final Privacy Rule, 45 CFR Part 164.514(h), Department of Health and Human Services, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/</a> August 14, 2002.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:215:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security/Privacy Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0);
