(13, 13, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:13:"<p>ECP-17</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:130:"<p>The purpose is to provide guidance to PIPL Clients and personnel regarding prohibition of intimidation or retaliatory acts.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:186:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, and temporary workers.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:876:"<p>PIPL personnel will not intimidate, threaten, coerce, discriminate against, or take other retaliatory action against, a Client for the exercise by that individual, of any right under the HIPAA Privacy Regulations, or for participation by the Client in any process established by the Privacy Regulations.</p><p>Note: This prohibition applies to any individual filing a complaint with the United States Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS); testifying, assisting, or participating in an investigation, compliance review, proceeding, or hearing arising under the Privacy Regulations; or opposing any act or practice of PIPL, provided the individual or person has a good faith belief that the practice opposed is unlawful, and the manner of opposition is reasonable and does not disclose Protected Health Information (PHI) in violation of the Privacy Regulations.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:9:"Procedure";s:5:"des_8";s:1792:"<ol><li>Consistent with PIPL&rsquo;s intention to encourage regulatory compliance and improved Client care through an accessible and well-documented complaint process, PIPL will have no tolerance for acts of intimidation, threats, coercion, discrimination, or other retaliatory behavior against persons attempting in good faith, and in a reasonable manner, to exercise their rights concerning the privacy of health information.</li><li>As part of its compliance education program, the Compliance Office is responsible for educating all PIPL personnel of the prohibition against intimidating, threatening, coercive, discriminatory, or retaliatory action against persons exercising their rights or participating in any process concerning the privacy of health information.&nbsp;</li><li>Any reports of suspected intimidating, threatening, discriminatory or retaliatory acts taken toward Clients or PIPL personnel should be reported to the Compliance Office <strong>immediately</strong>.</li><li>The Compliance Office will investigate fully any complaint or allegation of the intimidating, discriminatory, or retaliatory behavior.&nbsp; Upon completion of this investigation, if the Chief Compliance Officer finds that the intimidating, discriminatory, or retaliatory behavior did occur, he/she will take appropriate action against the responsible personnel, up to and including termination.</li><li>If PIPL personnel has filed a complaint with DHHS, testified, assisted, or participated in an investigation, or opposed any act or practice such personnel believe to be unlawful, the Chief Compliance Officer, will consult with, if necessary, Human Resources, Risk Management, and/or legal counsel before reaching any final decisions concerning the employment of the involved personnel.</li></ol>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:255:"<p>All individuals identified in the scope of this policy are responsible for meeting the requirements of this policy.</p><p>The PIPL Privacy Officer is responsible for maintaining this policy and communicating this policy to members of the workforce.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:336:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention. Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:262:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other privacy policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as the HIPAA Privacy Rule and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:1783:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>HIPAA Final Privacy Rule, 45 CFR Part 164.514(h), Department of Health and Human Services, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/</a> August 14, 2002.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:220:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, CEO, Information Security/Privacy Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(14, 14, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:13:"<p>ECP-18</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:167:"<p>The purpose is to require each member of the PIPL workforce to follow confidentiality requirements and to sign the PIPL Acknowledgement of Confidentiality form.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:182:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:1892:"<p><strong>Confidential Client Information</strong></p><ol><li>Workforce members will keep all information concerning the Covered Entity&rsquo;s Clients confidential.&nbsp; They will access, use, and disclose a Client&rsquo;s Protected Health Information (PHI) only for payment, treatment, and health care operation purposes&mdash;unless permitted by PIPL HIPAA policies.a</li><li>PIPL respects Clients&rsquo;, employees&rsquo;, and physicians&rsquo; rights to privacy and confidentiality.&nbsp; Workforce members will be sensitive to the privacy needs of PIPL Clients, and will conduct communications involving Client care and PHI in compliance with the procedures set forth in this policy.</li><li>Advances in technology are making it easier to use and disclose Client information.&nbsp; Workforce members must ensure that any transmission of Client information, including photographs or images of Clients, Clients&rsquo; families, or Client documents, comply with existing policies concerning the appropriate use and disclosure of Protected Health Information, including the PIPL Policy on Network Usage.</li></ol><p><strong>Confidential PIPL Information</strong></p><p>Workforce members will keep all confidential information concerning PIPL business operations, confidential.&nbsp; They will access, use and disclose this information only as expressly allowed by PIPL policy or by the PIPL Administrative Team.</p><p><strong>Workforce Confidentiality Agreement</strong></p><p>All workforce members will sign, and PIPL will maintain the signed PIPL Acknowledgement of Confidentiality form.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Workforce Member Orientation</strong></p><p>Orientation of all new workforce members will include instruction concerning this confidentiality policy, the PIPL policies concerning use and disclosure of Client PHI and Client rights, and the required confidentiality agreement.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:9:"Procedure";s:5:"des_8";s:5581:"<p><strong>General Confidentiality</strong></p><ol><li>During the course of employment, certain workforce members will have access to confidential employee, payroll, physician, and other business data.&nbsp; Workforce members with access to such information are responsible for keeping such information confidential and secure.</li><li>Any workforce member who intentionally breaches the security or confidentiality of Client, employee, physician, or payroll information, or who seeks confidential information for personal curiosity, photocopying, discussing, or in any way disseminating such information inside or outside of the company will be liable for disciplinary action up to and including termination.</li></ol><p><strong>Email Communications</strong></p><ol><li>Anyone communicating by email must be cognizant that email messages can be forwarded or read by other than the intended recipient and should edit the content of their email messages appropriately.&nbsp; All email should comply with the standards set forth in PIPL policy on email.</li><li>Information that is confidential and privileged based upon applicable federal and state law.</li></ol><p><strong>Medical Record Confidentiality</strong><a id="_anchor_1" href="#_msocom_1" name="_msoanchor_1">[NK1]</a>&nbsp;</p><ol><li>The medical record is the property of the respective PIPL facility (hospital, family health center) and shall be maintained to serve the Client, health providers, and the facilities in accordance with legal, accrediting, and regulatory requirements.</li><li>The information contained in the medical record belongs to the Client and the Client is entitled to have this information protected.&nbsp; All Client information shall be regarded as confidential and made available only to those authorized by the Client or his/her legal representative unless otherwise permitted by PIPL policies and procedures on HIPAA.</li><li>Each PIPL site shall have a department/individual that is responsible for medical records.&nbsp; Coordination of releases of medical record information will be done through the Medical Records Department.</li><li>Original medical records may not be removed from the premises of any PIPL facility except in accordance with a court order.</li><li>The Client&rsquo;s medical record may be read only by PIPL workforce members or medical staff who are directly involved in payment, treatment or health care operations concerning the Client.&nbsp; Access to such records must be limited to the minimum necessary to accomplish the intended purpose.&nbsp; Inappropriate access to any Client record is grounds for immediate termination.</li></ol><p><strong>Destruction of Copied or Printed Confidential Information</strong></p><p>Any copies or print-outs of medical records will be controlled by the person making or printing the copy and destroyed in the above-mentioned manner.&nbsp; All copied documents containing Client information or documents printed will be placed in the locked Confidential Bin to be shredded.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Acknowledgement of Confidentiality Form</strong></p><p>The Acknowledgement of Confidentiality form is available by contacting the Compliance Office.&nbsp; Other resource locations may be made available later.</p><p><strong>Employees</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All employees will sign a confidentiality form prior to employment as part of new employee packet.&nbsp; The signed confidentiality form will be maintained in the employee personnel file.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; PIPL Information Technology will require evidence prior to distributing user names and passwords that employees who require access to the PIPL network have signed and returned the Acknowledgement of Confidentiality form.</p><p><strong>Temporary Employees</strong></p><p>Any temporary employee who has access to confidential PIPL information or PHI will need to sign the Acknowledgement of Confidentiality.&nbsp; Department managers who utilize temporary employees will download the Acknowledgement of Confidentiality form and ask the employee to sign the form.&nbsp; Once the form is signed, the form is to be sent interoffice to the Information Technology Department to activate the user account and for filing.</p><p><strong>Volunteers</strong></p><p>All volunteers will sign the Acknowledgement of Confidentiality form and return it to the Volunteer Office prior to beginning volunteer service. &nbsp;The Volunteer Office will retain the signed Acknowledgement of Confidentiality in the volunteer files.&nbsp; For those volunteers who require access to the PIPL network, a copy of the signed Acknowledgement of Confidentiality form will be provided to the PIPL Information Technology Department.</p><p><strong>Non-PIPL Personnel on PIPL Property</strong></p><ol><li>Non-PIPL personnel who are working on PIPL property and who have access to confidential PIPL information or PHI will sign the Acknowledgement of Confidentiality form.&nbsp; Once the form is signed, the form is to be sent interoffice to the Compliance Office for filing.</li><li>This does not apply to individuals who are covered under a Business Associate Agreement between PIPL and a contractor unless the individuals require access to the PIPL network to perform their duties. All individuals who require access to the PIPL network will sign the Acknowledgement of Confidentiality form. Once the form is signed, the form is to be sent interoffice to the Information Technology (IT) Department for activation of the user account and for filing.</li></ol>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:255:"<p>All individuals identified in the scope of this policy are responsible for meeting the requirements of this policy.</p><p>The PIPL Privacy Officer is responsible for maintaining this policy and communicating this policy to members of the workforce.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:336:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention. Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:262:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other privacy policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as the HIPAA Privacy Rule and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:41:"<p>Acknowledgement of Confidentiality</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:1783:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>HIPAA Final Privacy Rule, 45 CFR Part 164.514(h), Department of Health and Human Services, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/</a> August 14, 2002.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:220:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, CEO, Information Security/Privacy Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(15, 15, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:13:"<p>ECP-19</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:203:"<p>The purpose is to establish a process for reporting a breach of Protected Health Information (PHI) privacy or a PHI (or electronic PHI &ndash; EPHI) security incident to the affected organization.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:186:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, and temporary workers.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:276:"<p>Consistent with its mission, contractual obligations, and the requirements of HIPAA and the HITECH Act, PIPL policy provides for safeguarding the privacy and security of PHI, and reporting to the affected organization any breach of PHI privacy or PHI security incident.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:9:"Procedure";s:5:"des_8";s:2712:"<p><strong>Employees/Authorized Individuals:</strong></p><ol><li>Report to Department Head any suspected privacy breach or security incident as soon as it is detected or suspected.</li></ol><p><strong>Department Head:</strong></p><ol><li>Report to Compliance and Privacy Officer any suspected privacy breach as soon as it is detected or reported by a member of the workforce.</li><li>Report to Information Security Officer any suspected security incident as soon as it is detected or reported by a member of the workforce.</li></ol><p><strong>Compliance and Privacy and Information Security Officers:</strong></p><ol><li>Investigate all relevant facts, entities and individuals involved to determine whether there is sufficient information to support a reasonable conclusion that a breach of privacy and/or a security incident has occurred.</li><li>If it is concluded that a privacy breach and/or security incident has occurred, determine the steps necessary to mitigate, to the extent practicable, any potential harmful effect of the breach or incident.</li></ol><p><strong>President, General Counsel, Compliance and Privacy and Information Security Officers:</strong></p><ol><li>Report to the affected organization the nature and consequences of any material privacy breach or security incident.</li><li>The Information Security Officer, Privacy Officer, and legal counsel shall work together to determine state and federal laws that may be applicable to the incident, including but not limited to HIPAA, HITECH, and state breach notification regulations.</li><li>Recommend to the Corporate Compliance Council possible operational improvements to prevent recurrence of any privacy breach or security incident.</li><li>Refer any intentional employee privacy breach or security incident to Human Resources for handling consistent with disciplinary policies.</li><li>Treat any intentional contractor privacy breach or security incident as a breach of contract matter.</li><li>The Information Security Officer, the Privacy Officer, or the legal counsel will notify the Marketing and Communications Department prior to any public notices.</li><li>Required notifications will be made in the most expedient time possible and without unreasonable delay, but in no event will exceed 60 days unless law enforcement agencies request a delay as a part of their investigation process.</li></ol><p><strong>Corporate Compliance Council:</strong></p><ol><li>Review reports of any privacy breaches and security incidents provided by the Compliance and Privacy and Information Security Officers.</li><li>Recommend to Management operational improvements to prevent recurrence of any privacy breach or security incident.</li></ol>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:255:"<p>All individuals identified in the scope of this policy are responsible for meeting the requirements of this policy.</p><p>The PIPL Privacy Officer is responsible for maintaining this policy and communicating this policy to members of the workforce.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:336:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention. Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:262:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other privacy policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as the HIPAA Privacy Rule and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:1519:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>HIPAA Final Privacy Rule, 45 CFR Part 164.514(h), Department of Health and Human Services, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/</a> August 14, 2002.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:220:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, CEO, Information Security/Privacy Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(16, 16, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:13:"<p>ECP-20</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:132:"<p>The purpose is to ensure that PIPL employees safeguard Protected Health Information (PHI) when transmitting PHI by facsimile.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:186:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, and temporary workers.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:753:"<ol><li>It is the policy of PIPL to protect the privacy and confidentiality of PHI transmitted by facsimile (fax) and hold Employees responsible for following the proper procedure when PHI is sent via facsimile to members and customers. Facsimile transmissions should include the PIPL approved fax cover sheet containing a confidentiality statement. Employee must include at a minimum on the fax cover sheet the name and fax number to whom the fax is going to and the name and phone number of the person sending the fax.</li><li>PHI may be transmitted by facsimile pursuant to the PIPL privacy policies. Information transmitted must be limited to the minimum necessary to meet the requestor&rsquo;s needs. See ECP-03, Minimum Necessary Policy.</li></ol>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:9:"Procedure";s:5:"des_8";s:1364:"<p><strong>Outgoing Faxes</strong>:</p><ol><li>The fax cover sheet containing a confidentiality statement approved by the Privacy Officer must be used. The cover sheet must also contain directions for the recipient if he/she receives a misdirected fax.</li><li>Frequently dialed fax numbers should be programmed into the fax server and checked frequently to assure accuracy.</li><li>If the number dialed is not pre-programmed into the fax server, it should be double- checked for accuracy prior to sending the fax.</li></ol><p><strong>Incoming Faxes:</strong></p><p>Any fax received in error should be reported to the sender and disposed of as directed by the sender.</p><p><strong>Misdirected Faxes:</strong></p><ol><li>If a fax transmission containing PHI is not received by the intended recipient because of a misdial, check the internal logging system of the fax server to obtain the misdialed number.</li><li>If possible, a phone call should be made to the recipient of the misdirected fax requesting that the entire content of the misdirected fax be destroyed. If the recipient cannot be reached by phone, a fax should be sent to the recipient requesting that the entire fax transmission be destroyed.</li><li>Any instance of transmitting PHI to the wrong destination number must be tracked pursuant to the ECP-08, Accounting of Disclosures Policy.</li></ol>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:255:"<p>All individuals identified in the scope of this policy are responsible for meeting the requirements of this policy.</p><p>The PIPL Privacy Officer is responsible for maintaining this policy and communicating this policy to members of the workforce.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:336:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention. Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:262:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other privacy policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as the HIPAA Privacy Rule and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:1783:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>HIPAA Final Privacy Rule, 45 CFR Part 164.514(h), Department of Health and Human Services, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/</a> August 14, 2002.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:220:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, CEO, Information Security/Privacy Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(17, 17, 'a:48:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:13:"<p>ECP-21</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:328:"<p>The purpose is to accurately describe which identifiers are removed from the health information so that the health information cannot be traced to a specific individual and PIPL can use the de-identified health information without Client authorization. This policy is based on Section 164.514(a) of the HIPAA Privacy Rule</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:187:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to, full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, and temporary workers.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:270:"<p>Should PIPL need to share health information without Client authorization, all identifiable health information will be removed. To de-identify data, PIPL will follow either the Expert Determination or Safe Harbor method, depending on the data to be de-identified.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:11:"Definitions";s:5:"des_8";s:1829:"<p>Expert Determination: A person with appropriate knowledge of and experience with generally accepted statistical and scientific principles and methods for rendering information not individually identifiable:<br />&nbsp;</p><ol><li>Applying such principles and methods, determines that the risk is very small that the information could be used, alone or in combination with other reasonably available information, by an anticipated recipient to identify an individual who is a subject of the information, and</li><li>Documents the methods and results of the analysis that justify such determination</li></ol><p>Safe Harbor:</p><ol><li>Remove the following identifiers for the CE&rsquo;s Clients, or of relatives, employers, or household members of the Clients: names, geographic subdivisions smaller than a state; all elements of dates (except year) for dates that are directly related to an individual (and over age 89); telephone numbers; fax numbers; email addresses; Social Security number; medical record numbers; health plan beneficiary number; account numbers; certificate/license numbers;&nbsp; vehicle identifiers; device identifiers and serial numbers; URLs; IP addresses; biometric identifiers; full-face photographs and any comparable images; any other unique identifying number, characteristic, or code (with some exceptions), and</li><li>PIPL does not have actual knowledge that the information could be used alone or in combination with other information to identify the Client or individual who is a subject of the information.</li></ol><p>Expert: From an enforcement perspective, OCR would review the relevant professional experience and academic or other training of the expert used by the covered entity, as well as actual experience of the expert using health information de-identification methodologies.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:9:"Procedure";s:5:"des_9";s:4385:"<p>1. To satisfy the Expert Determination guidance, PIPL ensures that</p><ul><li>Statistical or scientific principles can be applied to the data to render it unidentifiable, and</li><li>There is a very small risk that the recipient could identify the CE&rsquo;s Clients.</li></ul><p>2.To satisfy the Safe Harbor guidance, PIPL ensures that it has removed 18 types of identifier and there is no actual knowledge in the residual information that can identify the individual:</p><ul><li>Names (name of Client, relatives, employer or household member)</li><li>Address, including street address, city, county, zip code (first three digits may be used if it represents more than 20,000 people)</li><li>All date elements related to a Client (birth date - the year element can be kept except for any age indicator for Clients over age 89 - for Clients over 89 the age may be aggregated into a 90 category)</li><li>Telephone numbers</li><li>Fax numbers</li><li>Email addresses</li><li>Social Security number</li><li>Medical record number</li><li>Health plan beneficiary number</li><li>Account numbers (including group number)</li><li>Certificate/license numbers</li><li>Vehicle identifiers (serial number, license plate, etc.)</li><li>Device identifiers and serial numbers</li><li>URLs (Web Universal Resource Locators)</li><li>IP (Internet Protocol) address</li><li>Biometric identifiers (fingerprints, voice print, etc.)</li><li>Full face photographic or comparable image</li><li>Any other unique identifying number, characteristic or code</li></ul><p>3. Release of information to previous recipients. Periodically, PIPL provides monthly reports to various recipients. Health information data must be adequately de-identified in these reports.</p><ul><li>PIPL will need to have an expert examine whether future releases of the data to the same recipient (e.g., monthly reporting) should be subject to additional or different de-identification processes consistent with current conditions to reach the very low risk requirement.&nbsp;</li></ul><p>4. In using the Safe Harbor method, use the following guidelines:</p><ul><li>An identifier listed in the Safe Harbor standard must be removed regardless of its location in the Client&rsquo;s record if it is recognizable as an identifier. This includes data in billing records, databases, and text fields (such as discharge summaries), for examples.</li><li>The year may be reported as a de-identified dates, such as 2009 instead of January 2, 2009.</li><li>Ages that are explicitly stated, or implied, as over 89 years old must be recorded as 90 or above.</li><li>Dates associated with test measures, such as a laboratory report, are directly related to a specific individual and relate to the provision of health care. Such dates are protected health information and cannot be reported under Safe Harbor.</li><li>Examples of &ldquo;any other unique identifying number, characteristic or code&rdquo;:&nbsp;</li></ul><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (i) Identifying number: clinical trial number</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (ii) Identifying characteristic:&nbsp; anything that distinguishes an individual and allows for&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; identification. For example, a unique identifying characteristic could be the occupation of a Client, if it&nbsp; was listed in a record as &ldquo;current President of State University.&rdquo;</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (iii) Identifying code: a code that could be derived from barcodes&nbsp;</p><ul><li>Only names of the individuals associated with the corresponding health information (i.e., the subjects of the records) and of their relatives, employers, and household members must be suppressed.</li><li>Names of CE&rsquo;s health care providers or workforce members do not need to be removed from the de-identified set.</li></ul><p>5. Refer to the following policies for specific uses and disclosures of de-identified data:</p><ul><li><a href="#Use_Discl_TPO">Use and Disclosure of PHI for Treatment, Payment and Health Care Operations Policy;</a></li><li><a href="#PHI_Research">Access, Use, Disclosure and Safeguarding PHI in the Conduct of Research Policy</a>, and</li><li><a href="#Identifying_PHI">Identifying PHI Policy</a>.</li></ul>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:6:"des_10";s:254:"<p>All individuals identified in the scope of this policy are responsible for meeting the requirements of this policy.<br />The PIPL Privacy Officer is responsible for maintaining this policy and communicating this policy to members of the workforce.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_11";s:336:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention. Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_12";s:262:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other privacy policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as the HIPAA Privacy Rule and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_13";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_14";s:1783:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>HIPAA Final Privacy Rule, 45 CFR Part 164.514(h), Department of Health and Human Services, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/</a> August 14, 2002.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_15";s:220:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, CEO, Information Security/Privacy Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";s:11:"subtitle_16";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_16";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_16";s:2:"16";}', '', '', 0);
