(18, 18, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:13:"<p>ECP-22</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:139:"<p>The purpose is to provide PIPL employees with the HIPAA Privacy Definitions for terms that may appear in the HIPAA Privacy Policies.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:186:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, and temporary workers.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:11:"Definitions";s:5:"des_7";s:17670:"<p><strong>Affiliated Covered Entity</strong>:</p><p>Legally separate Covered Entities that are affiliated may be designated as a single Covered Entity for purposes of HIPAA Privacy, if the separate entities are under common ownership or control.</p><p><strong>Business Associate:</strong></p><p>A business associate includes an entity that &lsquo;&lsquo;creates, receives, maintains, or transmits&rsquo;&rsquo; protected health information on behalf of a covered entity. Entities that maintain or store protected health information on behalf of a covered entity are business associates, even if they do not actually view the protected health information.</p><p>Examples of business associates are:</p><ul><li>Client Safety Organizations</li><li>Health Information Organizations</li><li>Vendors of Personal Health Records that require routine access to PHI</li><li>Persons who facilitate data transmission</li><li>Data storage company that has access to PHI (whether digital or hard copy), even if the entity does not view the information</li><li>Subcontractors that create, receive, maintain, or transmit PHI on behalf of the business associate.</li></ul><p><strong>Examples of Persons and Organizations Who Are Not Considered Business Associates</strong><strong>:</strong></p><p>Oversight agencies (OIG, CMS); a person or organization that acts merely as a conduit (a conduit transports information but does not access it, ex: United States Postal Service); financial institutions; health care provider; and an employee of a covered entity.</p><p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>&ldquo;Certain&rdquo; Health Care Operations:</p><p>&ldquo;Certain&rdquo; Health Care Operations means any of the following activities performed or undertaken by another Covered Entity which the Covered Entity is requesting a disclosure from PIPL.</p><p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Quality assessment and improvement activities, including outcomes evaluation and development of clinical guidelines</p><p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Population-based activities relating to improving health or reducing health care costs, protocol development, case management and care coordination</p><p>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Contacting Clients regarding information about treatment alternatives</p><p>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reviewing the competence or qualifications of health care professionals</p><p>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Evaluating provider performance</p><p>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Evaluating health plan performance</p><p>7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Accreditation</p><p>8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Certification</p><p>9.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Licensing</p><p>10.&nbsp; Credentialing</p><p>11.&nbsp; Health care fraud and abuse detection or compliance</p><p><strong>&nbsp;Covered Entities:</strong></p><p>Health plans, health care clearinghouses and health care providers.</p><p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>De-identification (De-identified):</p><p>See ECP-21, De-Identification Policy.</p><p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>Designated Record Set:</p><p>See ECP-04, Designation of Record Sets Policy.</p><p>Disclosure (Disclose):</p><p>Release, transfer, provide of access to, or divulge in any other manner of information outside of PIPL.</p><p><strong>Electronic Media:</strong></p><p>Includes any electronic storage material as defined by NIST. Thus &ldquo;intranets&rdquo; come within the definition. PHI stored, whether intentionally or not, in a photocopier, facsimile, and other devices is subject to the Privacy and Security Rules. Exception: If the information exchanged by facsimile did <em>not</em> exist in electronic form <em>immediately</em> before transmission, that information is <em>not</em> electronic media.</p><p><strong>&nbsp;Employee:</strong></p><p>For purposes of the Privacy policies, the definition of employee includes all members of the PIPL workforce, including interns and temporary personnel. See also &ldquo;Workforce Member&rdquo; below.</p><p><strong>Group Health Plan:</strong></p><p>An employee welfare benefit plan defined in section 3(1) of ERISA, 29 U.S.C. 1002(1), including insured and self-insured plans to the extent that the plan provides medical coverage to employees or their dependents directly or through insurance, reimbursement or otherwise and that has 50 or more participants or is administered by an entity other than the employer that established and maintains the plan.</p><p><strong>Health Care Operations:</strong></p><p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Health Care Operations means any of the following activities performed or undertaken by PIPL:</p><ul><li>Conducting quality assessment and improvement activities</li><li>Accreditation</li><li>Credentialing</li><li>Certification</li><li>Case management</li><li>Licensing</li><li>Evaluating health plan performance</li><li>Client safety activities as defined in the PSQIA</li><li>Prohibition on using or disclosing genetic information for underwriting purposes</li><li>Insurance activities relating to the renewal of a contract for insurance:</li></ul><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; i.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Underwriting</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ii.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Premium rating</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; iii.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Other activities relating to the creation, renewal or replacement of a contract for health&nbsp; insurance or health benefits, as well as ceding, securing or placing a contract for reinsurance of risk relating to claims for health care (including stop-loss and excess loss insurance)</p><p>Note: A group health plan that wants to replace its insurance carrier may disclose certain PHI to insurance issuers in order to obtain bids on new coverage, and an insurance carrier interested in bidding on new business may use PHI obtained from the potential new Client to develop the product and price.</p><ul><li>Conducting or arranging for medical review</li><li>Auditing functions, including fraud and abuse detection and compliance programs</li><li>Conducting or arranging for legal services</li><li>Business planning and development, such as conducting cost-management and planning-related analyses related to managing and operating the entity, including formulary development and administration, development or improvement of methods of payment or coverage policies.</li><li>Business management activities and general administrative functions, such as:</li></ul><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; i.&nbsp; Management activities relating to implementation of and compliance with the&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; requirements for Health Care Operations</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ii. Customer Service, including the provisions of data analyses for policyholders, Plan&nbsp;&nbsp; Sponsors or other customers, provided that PHI is not disclosed to such policyholder, Plan Sponsor or customer</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; iii.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Resolution of internal grievances (includes quality of care and internal employee complaints)</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; iv.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Due diligence in connection with the sale or transfer of assets to a potential successor in interest, if the potential successor in interest is a Covered Entity or, following completion of the sale or transfer, will become a Covered Entity</p><p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Activities that would not be considered Health Care Operations:</p><ul><li>Marketing of health and non-health items and services</li><li>Disclosure of PHI for sale, rent or barter</li><li>Use of PHI by a non-health related division of an entity</li><li>Disclosure to an employer for employment determinations</li></ul><p><strong>Health Information:</strong></p><p>Any information, whether oral or recorded in any form or medium, that:</p><p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Is created or received by a health care provider, health plan, public health authority, employer, life insurer, school, university or health care clearinghouse.</p><p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Relates to the past, present or future physical or mental health or condition of a Client; the provision of health care to a Client; or past, present or future payment for the provision of health care to a Client.</p><p>&ldquo;Health Information&rdquo; includes genetic information.</p><p><strong>&nbsp;Health Plan:</strong></p><p>An individual or group plan that provides or pays the cost of medical care, including church plans and government plans. (Any plan to which creditable coverage applies.)</p><p><strong>&nbsp;Individually Identifiable Health Information:</strong></p><p>Information that is a subset of health information, including demographic information, collected from a Client and that:</p><p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Is created by or received by a Covered Entity.</p><p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Relates to the past, present or future physical or mental health or condition of a Client, the provision of health care to a Client or past, present or future payment for the provision of health care to a Client:</p><p>A.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Which identifies the Client.</p><p>B.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; With respect to which there is a reasonable basis to believe that the information can be used to identify the Client.</p><p><strong>Personal Representative:</strong></p><p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A person has authority to act on behalf of a Client who is an adult or an emancipated minor in making decisions related to health care.</p><p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An executor, administrator or other person has authority to act on behalf of a deceased Client or of the Client&#39;s estate.</p><p>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A parent, guardian or other person acting in loco parentis, has authority to act on behalf of a Client who is an unemancipated minor in making decisions related to health care (this includes appointed representatives under a qualified medical child support order (QMCSO).</p><p><strong>Organized Health Care Arrangement:</strong></p><p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A clinically integrated care setting in which Clients typically receive health care from more than one health care provider.</p><p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An organized system of health care in which more than one Covered Entity participates, and in which the participating Covered Entities hold themselves out to the public as participating in a joint arrangement and participate in joint activities that include at least one of the following:</p><p>A.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Utilization review, in which health care decisions by participating Covered Entities are reviewed by other participating Covered Entities or by a third party on their behalf.</p><p>B.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Quality assessment and improvement activities, in which treatment provided by participating Covered Entities is assessed by other participating Covered Entities or by a third party on their behalf.</p><p>C.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Payment activities, if the financial risk for delivering health care is shared, in part or in whole, by participating Covered Entities through the joint arrangement and if PHI created or received by a Covered Entity is reviewed by other participating Covered Entities or by a third party on their behalf for the purpose of administering the sharing of financial risk.</p><p>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A Group Health Plan and a health insurance issuer or HMO with respect to such Group Health Plan, but only with respect to PHI created or received by such health insurance issuer or HMO that relates to Clients who are or who have been participants or beneficiaries in such Group Health Plan.</p><p>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A Group Health Plan and one or more other Group Health Plans each of which are maintained by the same Plan Sponsor.</p><p>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Group Health Plans described in number 4 directly above and health insurance issuers or HMOs with respect to such Group Health Plans, but only with respect to PHI created or received by such health insurance issuers or HMOs that relates to Clients who are or have been participants or beneficiaries in any of such Group Health Plans.</p><p><strong>&nbsp;Payment:</strong></p><p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The activities undertaken:</p><ul><li>To obtain premiums or determine or fulfill our responsibilities for coverage and provision of benefits.</li><li>To obtain or provide reimbursement for the provision of health care.</li></ul><p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The activities that relate to the Client receiving the health care, include but are not limited to:</p><ul><li>Determinations of eligibility or coverage (including coordination of benefits) and adjudication or subrogation of health benefit claims</li><li>Adjusting premium amounts due based on enrollee health status and demographic characteristics (this is aggregate data used to rate an entire group)</li><li>Billing, claims management, collection activities, obtaining payment under a contract for reinsurance (including stop-loss)</li><li>Medical necessity review</li><li>Utilization review activities (preauthorization)</li></ul><p>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; PIPL may disclose to consumer reporting agencies any of the following PHI relating to collection of premiums or reimbursement: a Client&rsquo;s name, address, date of birth, social security number and payment history, account number, as well as the name and address of the Client&rsquo;s health care provider and/or health plan.</p><p><strong>Plan Sponsor</strong>:</p><p>Plan Sponsor is defined in section 3(16) (B) of ERISA, 29 U.S.C. 1002(16) (B). The Plan Sponsor is the employer or employee organization in the case of an employer benefit plan established or maintained by an employer (includes church and government plans). The Plan Sponsor is responsible for setting up the plan, regulatory reports, retains the right to amend the plan and signs official documents of the plan. The Plan Sponsor is limited to assigned responsibilities.</p><p><strong>&nbsp;Protected Health Information (PHI):</strong></p><p>All individually identifiable health information transmitted or maintained by a Covered Entity, regardless of form.</p><p>The HIPAA Privacy and Security Rules do not protect the individually identifiable health information of persons who have been deceased for more than 50 years.</p><p><strong>Psychotherapy Notes</strong>:</p><p>Notes recorded by a health care provider who is a mental health professional documenting conversation during a private counseling session or a group, joint or family counseling session. The information must be separated from the rest of the Client&rsquo;s medical record.</p><p><strong>Subcontractor</strong>:</p><p>A person who acts on behalf of a business associate, other than in the capacity of a member of the workforce of such business associate. The covered entity is not required to have a contract with the subcontractor. The business associate is required to obtain satisfactory assurances from the subcontractor in the form of a written contract or other arrangement that a subcontractor will appropriately safeguard PHI.</p><p><strong>Treatment:</strong></p><p>The provision, coordination or management of health care and related services by one or more health care providers, including the coordination or management of health care by a health care provider with a third party; consultation between health care providers relating to a Client; or the referral of a Client for health care from one health care provider to another.</p><p><strong>&nbsp;Underwriting Purposes:</strong></p><p>In this context, &ldquo;underwriting&rdquo; refers to a group health plan, health insurance coverage, or Medicare supplemental policy. Examples of &ldquo;underwriting purposes&rdquo; are:</p><p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Rules for, or determination of, eligibility (including enrollment and continued eligibility) for, or determination of, benefits under the plan, coverage, or policy. This includes changes in deductibles or other cost-sharing mechanisms in return for activities such as completing a health risk assessment or participating in a wellness program.</p><p>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The computation of premium or contribution amounts under the plan, coverage, or policy.</p><p>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Includes discounts, rebates, payments in kind, or other premium differential mechanisms in return for activities such as completing a health risk assessment or participating in a wellness program.</p><p>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The application of any pre-existing condition exclusion under the plan, coverage, or policy.</p><p>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Other activities related to the creation, renewal, or replacement of a contract of health insurance or health benefits.</p><p>&ldquo;Underwriting Purposes&rdquo; does not include determinations of medical appropriateness where an individual seeks a benefit under the plan, coverage, or policy.</p><p>Use:</p><p>The employment, application, utilization, examination or analysis of individually identifiable health information within an entity that maintains the information.</p><p><strong>Workforce Member:</strong></p><p>The term includes the employees, volunteers, trainees, and other persons whose conduct, in the performance of work for a covered entity or a business associate and is under the direct control of the covered entity or business associate.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_8";s:253:"<p>ll individuals identified in the scope of this policy are responsible for meeting the requirements of this policy.<br />The PIPL Privacy Officer is responsible for maintaining this policy and communicating this policy to members of the workforce.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:9:"Retention";s:5:"des_9";s:336:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention. Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_10";s:262:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other privacy policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as the HIPAA Privacy Rule and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_11";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_12";s:1783:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>HIPAA Final Privacy Rule, 45 CFR Part 164.514(h), Department of Health and Human Services, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/</a> August 14, 2002.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_13";s:220:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, CEO, Information Security/Privacy Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_14";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:0:"";s:6:"des_15";s:0:"";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(19, 19, 'a:39:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-201</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>13.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:120:"<p>The purpose is to implement policies and procedures to prevent, detect, contain, and correct security violations.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:454:"<p>This policy applies to Pabrai India Private Limited (PIPL) in its entirety, including all employees, workforce members, physicians and affiliates.&nbsp; In addition, some third parties such as contractors or vendors may be required to abide by parts of this policy if required by PIPL in a Business Associate Contract (BAC).&nbsp; Further, the policy applies to the network, systems and applications that process, store or transmit corporate data.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:5122:"<p>PIPL will create, administer and oversee policies that address the full range of security issues and ensure the prevention, detection, containment and correction of security violations.</p><p>PIPL will identify core activities in the areas of risk analysis, risk management, sanctions and information system activity review.</p><p>PIPL will establish management controls, electronic controls, physical security controls and penalties for the abuse and misuse of its assets, as well as corporate data.</p><ol><li>Risk Analysis: The identification, definition and prioritization of risks to PIPL&rsquo;s information systems must be based on a formal, documented risk analysis process.&nbsp; The risk analysis must be used in conjunction with PIPL&rsquo;s risk management process.&nbsp; A risk analysis process shall be conducted at least once annually for systems under the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) scope; periodically for systems under the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) of 1996 scope; and when environmental or operational changes occur which significantly impact the confidentiality, integrity or availability of specific information systems containing corporate data.</li></ol><p>PIPL must implement security controls to reduce risks and vulnerabilities to a reasonable and appropriate level.&nbsp; Both the probability and the impact of occurrence will be measured when defining a risk.</p><p>All risk analysis activities that are to be implemented are organized into three phases; the documentation phase, risk assessment phases and safeguard determination phase.</p><p>The results of all identified risk analysis activities along with the safeguard and other recommendations must be summarized with supporting documentation in a Risk Analysis report.</p><ol><li>Risk Management: PIPL will conduct risk management activities on a continuous basis.&nbsp; PIPL will select and implement reasonable, appropriate and cost-effective security measures to manage, mitigate or accept identified risks. Selection and implementation of such security measures must be based on a formal, document risk management process.</li></ol><p>The objective of performing risk management is to enable PIPL to accomplish its mission by:</p><ol><li>Better securing systems that store, process or transmit sensitive corporate data</li><li>Enabling management to make well-informed decisions to justify the expenditures that are a part of the IT and other budgets</li><li>By assisting management in authorizing or evaluating systems on the basis of supporting documentation resulting from the performance of risk management</li></ol><p>At a minimum, the risk management process must include the following:</p><p>a.&nbsp;&nbsp; Workforce member training and awareness on implemented security measures b.&nbsp;&nbsp; Evaluation and revision, as necessary, of existing security measures</p><p>One or more of the following methods to manage risk shall be used: risk acceptance, risk avoidance, risk reduction or risk transfer.</p><p>Risk management activities at PIPL shall consist of three phases: risk assessment, risk mitigation and evaluation and assessment.</p><p>The IT Security Department must be supported by all system owners, data owners and other managers to identify and prioritize risks to sensitive corporate data.</p><p>Risk management is an essential management function at PIPL.</p><ol><li>Sanctions: PIPL will apply appropriate sanctions against workforce members who fail to comply with PIPL security policies and procedures as per the PIPL Employee Handbook section <em>Non-Compliance Sanctions</em>.</li></ol><p>4.&nbsp;&nbsp; Information System Activity Review: PIPL must use appropriate means to detect vulnerabilities and potential risks to the improper disclosure of Electronic Protected Health Information (EPHI). &nbsp;PIPL must implement procedures to regularly review records of information system activity, such as audit logs, access reports and security incident reports.&nbsp; These procedures should contain the following components:</p><ol><li>The IT Security Department will be responsible for the assessment or delegation of system activity review</li><li>PIPL will define a regular review cycle of information system activity</li><li>The HIPAA Security Officer will be able to review system activity in response to security incident notifications or other suspicious events</li></ol><p>When determining the responsibility for information review, a separation of roles should be considered between the person(s) undertaking the review and those whose activities are being monitored.</p><p>In the area of Information System Activity Review, PIPL will seek to record and review the following activities for systems that collect, store, process or transmit corporate data:</p><ol><li>Who (Unique User ID), did</li><li>What (Read, print, write, edit, delete, etc.), to</li><li>What data (Server, DB, instance, table, row, field), d.&nbsp;&nbsp; When (Enterprise-wide timestamp), and from</li><li>Where (IP address, terminal ID, local or remote)</li></ol>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:9:"Retention";s:5:"des_8";s:341:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.<br />Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:10:"Compliance";s:5:"des_9";s:275:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.<br />Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, GLB, Sarbanes-Oxley, PCI DSS and others.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_10";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_11";s:1562:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services: &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_12";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_13";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";}', '', '', 0),
(20, 20, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-206</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>13.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:210:"<p>The purpose of this policy is to identify the security official who is responsible for the development and implementation of the policies and procedures required by the HIPAA Security Rule 164.308(a)(2).</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:98:"<p>This policy applies to PIPL in its entirety, including all employees and workforce members.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:1720:"<p>PIPL will assign final responsibility of security to one individual who will be referred to as the &ldquo;Information Security Officer.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p><p>This individual&rsquo;s ultimate goal is to protect the confidentiality, integrity, and availability (CIA) of critical information assets at PIPL and to ensure compliance with applicable regulations.</p><p>Responsibilities of the Information Security Officer include (but are not limited to):</p><ul><li>Ensuring all policies, procedures, and plans required by regulations are developed, implemented, and maintained as necessary.</li><li>Monitoring changes in legislation that may affect PIPL and its security position.</li><li>Monitoring changes and advances in technology that may affect PIPL and its security position.</li><li>Performing technical and non-technical evaluations or audits on security processes in order to find and correct weaknesses and guard against potential threats to security.</li><li>Acting as an internal consultant and potentially as an external spokesperson for PIPL in all issues related to security.</li><li>Ensuring a system for reporting and responding to security incidents (as well as violations of regulations) is in place and functioning.</li><li>Delivering, on an ongoing basis, security awareness training to all members of the workforce.</li></ul><p>If the Information Security Officer is not able to meet the requirements of this policy, or is no longer affiliated with the organization, PIPL will assign these responsibilities to a new Information Security Officer.&nbsp; The appointment will not be left unfilled and will be documented with the Information Security Officer Declaration Log and organizational chart.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_8";s:756:"<p>All individuals, groups, and organizations identified in the scope of this policy are responsible for:</p><ul><li>Supporting and providing assistance to the Information Security Officer whenever necessary when the Information Security Officer is acting in the role described under the policy section.</li></ul><p>The PIPL Information Security Officer, as defined by the Assigned Security Responsibility Policy, is responsible for all aforementioned responsibilities described in the policy section.</p><p>All management members are responsible for:</p><ul><li>Duly appointing a capable Information Security Officer and replacing that person if they are not able to fill their responsibilities or are no longer affiliated with the organization.</li></ul>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:10:"Compliance";s:5:"des_9";s:259:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp;<br />Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, HITECH and others.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_10";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_11";s:1781:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services: &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_12";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_13";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:0:"";s:6:"des_14";s:0:"";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:0:"";s:6:"des_15";s:0:"";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(21, 21, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-207</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>13.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:243:"<p>PIPL will implement policies and procedures to ensure that all members of the workforce have appropriate access to corporate data and to prevent those workforce members who should not have access from obtaining access to corporate data.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:423:"<p>This policy applies to PIPL in its entirety, including all employees, workforce members, physicians and affiliates.&nbsp; In addition, some third parties such as contractors or vendors may be required to abide by parts of this policy if required by PIPL in a Business Associate Contract (BAC).&nbsp; Further, the policy applies to the network, systems and applications that process, store or transmit corporate data.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:3932:"<p>Access to PIPL information systems will only be provided to authorize members of the workforce, and all such information access shall be restricted to the minimum necessary to accomplish their job role or function.</p><p>The termination of any member of the workforce will result in the implementation of the activities defined in Termination Procedures.</p><p>All members of the workforce will be appropriately trained so they understand PIPL&rsquo;s policies relating to accessing authorized information only.</p><p>PIPL will continuously assess potential risks and vulnerabilities to corporate data in its possession and develop, implement and maintain appropriate security controls.</p><ol><li>Authorization and/or Supervision: Implement procedures for the authorization and/or supervision of workforce members who work with corporate data or in locations where it may be accessed.&nbsp; PIPL will implement security safeguards to ensure that all members of the workforce require the access they have, have the access they need, understand the limits of their access to corporate data and understand how to authenticate themselves to the systems or applications.</li></ol><p>The determination if any access needs to be supervised must be based on the results and recommendations of the Risk Analysis report.</p><p>Authorization and/or Supervision activities shall include the supervision of some members of the workforce, the proper access authorizations on the basis of job roles or functions, clearance procedures and maintenance of access authorization records.</p><ol><li>Workforce Clearance Procedure: Implement procedures to determine that the access of a workforce member to corporate data is appropriate.&nbsp; Effective personnel screening procedures will be applied to allow a range of implementation, from minimal procedures to more stringent procedures, based on the results of the risk analysis performed.&nbsp; Under Ohio Law, and hospital licensing and accreditation mandates, certain applicants must consent to a criminal background check and fingerprinting. &nbsp;For those employees that are required to be licensed by law, or claim to be licensed in a specific field, the applicant must show proof of his/her license and/or registration number. &nbsp;PIPL will check applicants and current members of the workforce against the Department of Health and Human Services Office of Inspector General (OIG) Exclusion List.&nbsp; PIPL will also check an applicant&rsquo;s references and background prior to offering employment to an applicant.</li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p><p>3. Termination Procedures: Implement procedures for quickly, securely and appropriately terminating access to all systems and corporate data when the relationship between a workforce member and PIPL ends.&nbsp; PIPL will ensure that the following controls are in place:</p><p>a.&nbsp;&nbsp; Information systems access, both internal and remote, must be disabled or removed and confirmation is required to be communicated to the IT Security Department.</p><p>b.&nbsp;&nbsp; PIPL will maintain a checklist of supplied equipment and verify what needs to be returned.</p><p>c.&nbsp;&nbsp; PIPL shall specifically request the return of all corporate data in any format upon termination or separation.</p><p>d.&nbsp;&nbsp; Security access codes and/or passwords used to protect PIPL&rsquo;s corporate data that are known by departing workforce members will be changed within a time period appropriate to risk level and verified by the HIPAA Security Officer.</p><p>e.&nbsp;&nbsp; If workforce members are terminated immediately and pose a risk to PIPL&rsquo;s corporate data, their information system privileges must be removed or disabled before they are notified of the termination.</p><p>Additional information regarding workforce security can be found in the Employee Handbook.&nbsp; Go to the Intranet Home Page; Select Knowledge Management;</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:9:"Retention";s:5:"des_8";s:342:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p><p>Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:10:"Compliance";s:5:"des_9";s:276:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.</p><p>Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, GLB, Sarbanes-Oxley, PCI DSS and others.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_10";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_11";s:1781:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services: &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_12";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_13";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:0:"";s:6:"des_14";s:0:"";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:0:"";s:6:"des_15";s:0:"";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0);
