(38, 36, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-410</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>13.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:146:"<p>Implement security controls to guard against unauthorized access to corporate data that is being transmitted over a communications network.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:423:"<p>This policy applies to PIPL in its entirety, including all employees, workforce members, physicians and affiliates.&nbsp; In addition, some third parties such as contractors or vendors may be required to abide by parts of this policy if required by PIPL in a Business Associate Contract (BAC).&nbsp; Further, the policy applies to the network, systems and applications that process, store or transmit corporate data.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:1441:"<p>Implement security policies to identify core activities for the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act of 1996(HIPAA) Integrity Controls and Encryption implementation specifications.</p><p>1.&nbsp; <strong>Integrity Controls</strong>: PIPL will use appropriate integrity controls to protect the confidentiality, integrity and availability of corporate data transmitted over communications networks.</p><p>PIPL&rsquo;s integrity controls must ensure that the validity of all transmitted corporate data is maintained and the data is protected from unauthorized modification.&nbsp; The person(s) responsible for administering each information system and the IT Security Department will determine the appropriateness of controls based upon sensitivity of and risks of improper disclosure to corporate data.</p><p>2.&nbsp; <strong>Encryption</strong>: PIPL will implement encryption or other security controls to protect corporate data transmissions over open or private networks to ensure that such transmissions are not easily intercepted and interpreted by parties other than the intended recipient.&nbsp; PIPL&rsquo;s encryption key length requirement will be periodically reviewed and upgraded as deemed reasonable and appropriate. PIPL&rsquo;s encryption key lengths must be at least 128 bits.&nbsp; Proven algorithms such as DES, AES, Blowfish, RSA, RC5 and IDEA should be used as the basis for encryption technologies.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:9:"Retention";s:5:"des_8";s:342:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p><p>Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:10:"Compliance";s:5:"des_9";s:275:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.</p><p>Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, GLB, Sarbanes-Oxley, PCI DSS and others</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_10";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_11";s:2398:"<p><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></p><ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services: &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>NIST 800-113, Guide to SSL VPNs, <a href="http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-113/SP800-113.pdf">http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-113/SP800-113.pdf</a>.</li><li>NIST 800-77, Guide to IPsec VPSs, <a href="http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-77/sp800-77.pdf">http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-77/sp800-77.pdf</a>.</li><li>NIST 800-52, Guidelines for the Selection and Use of Transport Layer Security (TLS) Implementations, <a href="http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-52/SP800-52.pdf">http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-52/SP800-52.pdf</a>.</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_12";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_13";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:0:"";s:6:"des_14";s:0:"";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:0:"";s:6:"des_15";s:0:"";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(31, 29, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-306</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>13.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:303:"<p>The purpose is to implement policies and procedures that specify the proper functions to be performed, the manner in which those functions are to be performed, and the physical attributes of the surroundings of a specific workstation or class of workstation that can access sensitive information.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:476:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to sensitive information, such as sensitive information, by PIPL.&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition, this policy applies to all workstations and other computing devices owned or operated by PIPL and any computing device allowed to connect to PIPL&rsquo;s internal network.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:2582:"<p>PIPL will ensure that workstations and other computing devices are being used for work related purposes only.</p><p>All PIPL workstations will be utilized in a secure, approved manner, by authorized personnel only, and in such a way that the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of EPHI are not jeopardized.</p><p>PIPL will ensure that access is not permitted to PIPL workstations by individuals that are not authorized members of the PIPL workforce.</p><p>Workstations and other computing devices that are owned or operated by PIPL are to be used for work-related purposes only.&nbsp; This includes, but is not limited to, Internet and Web access as well as the use of email at PIPL.&nbsp;</p><p>Workforce members should not expect any level of personal privacy as their activities, emails, files, and logs may be viewed at any time by the Information Security Officer or other members of management in support of this and other policies and procedures.&nbsp;</p><p>PIPL may revoke the access rights of any individual at any time in order to protect or secure the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of sensitive information or to preserve the functionality of electronic information systems.</p><p>PIPL will implement reasonable and appropriate measures to secure its computing devices could be used to access sensitive information.&nbsp; These measures will include, but are not limited to the following:</p><ul><li>All user and administrator accounts must be protected by some form of authentication.&nbsp; If passwords are used, they must follow the guidelines set forth in ECP-409, Person or Entity Authentication Policy (Authentication Policy).</li><li>All users accessing PIPL&rsquo;s computing devices must have and use a unique user ID as set forth in the Authentication Policy.</li><li>Procedures must be maintained that implement security updates and software patches in a timely manner.</li><li>Procedures must be maintained that require users to run an up-to-date anti-virus program on all computing devices at PIPL.</li><li>All unnecessary and unused services (or ports) must be disabled.</li><li>Measures must be taken to physically protect computers that are located in public areas and portable computers, such as laptops and PDAs that could be removed from the premises.</li><li>Computers located in public areas will be situated as to block unauthorized viewing and/or will have screen savers that black out the screen. These computers will also have screen savers that automatically activate following a brief period of inactivity.</li></ul>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_8";s:107:"<p>The Information Security Officer will be responsible for ensuring the implementation of this policy.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:9:"Retention";s:5:"des_9";s:336:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention. Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_10";s:260:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp;</p><p>Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, HITECH and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_11";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_12";s:1781:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services: &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_13";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_14";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:0:"";s:6:"des_15";s:0:"";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(32, 30, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-307</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>13.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:126:"<p>Implement physical safeguards that restrict access to all workstations which access corporate data to authorized users.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:423:"<p>This policy applies to PIPL in its entirety, including all employees, workforce members, physicians and affiliates.&nbsp; In addition, some third parties such as contractors or vendors may be required to abide by parts of this policy if required by PIPL in a Business Associate Contract (BAC).&nbsp; Further, the policy applies to the network, systems and applications that process, store or transmit corporate data.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:1681:"<p>Workforce members must not use PIPL&rsquo;s workstations to engage in any activity that is either illegal under local, state, federal or international law, or is in violation of PIPL policy.</p><p>All members of the workforce will be trained on the appropriate and authorized use of workstations as part of their security awareness training.</p><p>Workstations will be positioned such that the monitor screens and keyboards are not within view of unauthorized individuals.</p><p>Users will lock or logoff prior to leaving a workstation unattended.&nbsp; Under no circumstance must any password information be accessible on the workstation or its vicinity.</p><p>Workstations must be labeled to identify function and location and assist with compliance with access control procedures.</p><p>All workstations must be operated in a manner that ensures:</p><ol><li>Confidentiality of corporate data</li><li>Display of an appropriate warning banner prior to gaining system access to critical systems</li><li>Employment of a password protected screen saver and/or workstation locking mechanism when the workstation is unattended</li><li>Proper shut down or restart of workstations should occur at the end of each business day to allow the device to receive required updates</li><li>Virus scanning of media prior to use on any workstation</li><li>Only PIPL provided software may be used on&nbsp; PIPL&rsquo;s workstations</li><li>Workstations and said software are used in accordance with contract agreements and copyright laws</li></ol><p>All members of the workforce must adhere to the PIPL General Computer Resource Acceptable Use Policy in addition to this policy.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:9:"Retention";s:5:"des_8";s:342:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p><p>Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:10:"Compliance";s:5:"des_9";s:276:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.</p><p>Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, GLB, Sarbanes-Oxley, PCI DSS and others.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_10";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_11";s:1781:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services: &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_12";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_13";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:0:"";s:6:"des_14";s:0:"";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:0:"";s:6:"des_15";s:0:"";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(34, 32, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-401</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>13.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:136:"<p>Implement procedures and controls for granting access to information systems containing corporate data to authorized individuals.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:423:"<p>This policy applies to PIPL in its entirety, including all employees, workforce members, physicians and affiliates.&nbsp; In addition, some third parties such as contractors or vendors may be required to abide by parts of this policy if required by PIPL in a Business Associate Contract (BAC).&nbsp; Further, the policy applies to the network, systems and applications that process, store or transmit corporate data.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:3573:"<p>PIPL will control access to its information systems and corporate data.</p><p>Only individuals that have been formally authorized to view or change corporate data will be granted access to that information.</p><p>Access to corporate data will be granted only if that individual has a legitimate business need.&nbsp; The fundamental principle of &ldquo;need to know&rdquo; will be applied within PIPL to determine access privileges.&nbsp; Reasonable efforts will be made to limit access to the minimum necessary needed to accomplish the intended purpose of the use, disclosure or request.</p><p>User accounts that have not authenticated, or connected to the network, in 180 days will be disabled.&nbsp; Computer objects that have not authenticated in 180 days will be deleted.</p><p><strong>1. Unique User Identification</strong>: PIPL will assign unique user credentials to identify and track the identity of individuals who access information systems and corporate data.</p><ul><li>User credentials must never be shared with anyone.</li><li>Users must use only their user credentials to access information systems and/or corporate data. &nbsp;In limited instances, a service account may need to be utilized by authorized personnel. &nbsp;In such cases, the accounts must be documented and, subsequently, each use of the account must be documented.</li><li>User credentials will remain with the individual throughout the entirety of their relationship with PIPL.</li><li>It is reasonable to anticipate that accounts will need to be created that are not uniquely associated with a specific user.&nbsp; These accounts must be unique to the process or function for which they are intended and must be documented.</li></ul><p><strong>2. Emergency Access Procedure</strong>: PIPL will establish Emergency Access Procedures for gaining access to corporate data during an emergency. Extraordinary care in safeguarding and documenting the use of the information will be exercised during this procedure. &nbsp;The configuration of emergency access controls will be consistent with approved authorizations.</p><p>PIPL will identify the necessary corporate data that would need to be obtained during an emergency.&nbsp; Such information will be consistent with that identified under Contingency Operations.</p><p>PIPL will test the emergency access controls to ensure availability and the appropriate restrictions.</p><p>In the event of an emergency, a record will be maintained of systems accessed.</p><p><strong>3. Automatic Logoff</strong>: PIPL will maintain electronic procedures for automatic logoff of systems that contain or access corporate data after a period of inactivity as defined in the Protection or Termination of Electronic Sessions Policy. 4.Encryption and Decryption: PIPL will evaluate and implement encryption and decryption solutions as a method of protecting data stored on systems that process corporate data.</p><p>PIPL will need to balance the challenge of protecting &ldquo;data at rest&rdquo; against the increase in security technology complexity and administrative overhead, including performance considerations and usability.</p><p>PIPL will review the viability of securing critical databases, file servers and corporate data on mobile devices.&nbsp; PIPL shall encrypt all PIPL-owned laptops that store corporate data.&nbsp; PIPL corporate data is not allowed to be stored, processed or transmitted on laptops not owned by PIPL.</p><p>PIPL will test encryption and decryption capabilities of products and systems to ensure proper functionality</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:9:"Retention";s:5:"des_8";s:342:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p><p>Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:10:"Compliance";s:5:"des_9";s:275:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.</p><p>Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, GLB, Sarbanes-Oxley, PCI DSS and others</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_10";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_11";s:2602:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services: &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_12";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_13";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:0:"";s:6:"des_14";s:0:"";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:0:"";s:6:"des_15";s:0:"";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(35, 33, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-406</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>13.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:374:"<p>To ensure security auditing capabilities on PIPL&rsquo;s information systems which contain or use corporate data, Audits will be conducted to ensure the confidentiality, integrity and availability of corporate data, investigate possible security incidents and ensure conformance to PIPL&rsquo;s security policies and monitor user or system activity where appropriate.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:425:"<p>This policy applies to PIPL in its entirety, including all employees, workforce members, physicians and affiliates.&nbsp; In addition, some third parties, such as contractors or vendors, may be required to abide by parts of this policy if required by PIPL in a Business Associate Contract (BAC).&nbsp; Further, the policy applies to the network, systems and applications that process, store or transmit corporate data.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:2342:"<p>Event auditing capabilities must be enabled on all systems that process, store or transmit corporate data.&nbsp; PIPL will audit who, did what, to what data, when and from where, whenever possible.&nbsp; On systems where these capabilities are not currently supported, a review will be conducted no less than every six months to determine if these capabilities can be added or configured, or are now supported by the vendor. The review and the results will be documented and retained.</p><p>Events to be audited may include, and are not limited to, logins, logouts and file accesses, deletions and modifications.</p><p>The person(s) responsible for administering each information system, such as the system owner, and the IT Security Department must develop and implement a formal process for audit log review.&nbsp; At a minimum, the process should include:</p><p>1. &nbsp;A definition of which workforce members will review records of activity</p><p>2. &nbsp;A definition of what activity is considered significant</p><p>3. &nbsp;Procedures defining how significant activity will be identified and reported</p><p>4. &nbsp;Procedures for preserving records of significant activity</p><p>PIPL workforce members should not review audit logs that pertain to their own system activity. &nbsp;When requested, and for the purpose of performing an audit, any access and/or support needed will be provided to the Privacy Officer, the HIPAA Security Officer and/or the IT Security Department.</p><p>This access may include:</p><p>1. &nbsp;User level and/or system level access to any computing or communications device</p><p>2. &nbsp;Access to information (e.g. electronic, hardcopy) that may be produced, transmitted or stored on PIPL&rsquo;s equipment or premises</p><p>3. &nbsp;Access to work areas (e.g. labs, offices, cubicles, storage areas)</p><p>4. &nbsp;Access to reports or, if authorized, interactively monitoring and logging traffic on</p><p>PIPL&rsquo;s networks</p><p>Safeguards must be deployed to protect against unauthorized changes and operational problems, even from privileged users, including:</p><p>1. &nbsp;Alterations to the message types that are being recorded</p><p>2. &nbsp;Log files being edited or deleted</p><p>3. &nbsp;Log file media becoming exhausted, and either failing to record events or overwriting itself</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:9:"Retention";s:5:"des_8";s:342:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p><p>Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:10:"Compliance";s:5:"des_9";s:276:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.</p><p>Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, GLB, Sarbanes-Oxley, PCI DSS and others.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_10";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_11";s:1781:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services: &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_12";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_13";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:0:"";s:6:"des_14";s:0:"";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:0:"";s:6:"des_15";s:0:"";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0);
