(36, 34, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-407</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>13.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:106:"<p>Implement policies and procedures to protect corporate data from improper alteration or destruction</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:423:"<p>This policy applies to PIPL in its entirety, including all employees, workforce members, physicians and affiliates.&nbsp; In addition, some third parties such as contractors or vendors may be required to abide by parts of this policy if required by PIPL in a Business Associate Contract (BAC).&nbsp; Further, the policy applies to the network, systems and applications that process, store or transmit corporate data.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:976:"<p>PIPL will protect corporate data from improper alteration or destruction.&nbsp; The files and associated directories where such data is stored will be checked for data integrity.</p><p>PIPL will works towards ensuring that all sensitive information systems are designed to maintain data integrity.</p><p>PIPL will train members of the workforce to report unauthorized data modification or destruction.</p><ol><li><strong>Mechanism to Authenticate Sensitive Information</strong>: Implement electronic mechanisms to validate that corporate data has not been altered or destroyed in any unauthorized manner.</li></ol><p>PIPL willviewtheuse f diil sntuend/or hksum thnoloyto onfim ht sensiive inomation has not ben lrd or strd in ay unuthorid mannr.</p><p>PIPL willvluatethe mpmentton ofnton to ensueteingiyof oporedta.</p><p>PIPL willstablish a slneof inoton to compre futuedaingiy hks gins.This yincludehking file and dirtoyonnts and tributs instafere, suchshksum mathin.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:9:"Retention";s:5:"des_8";s:342:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p><p>Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:10:"Compliance";s:5:"des_9";s:276:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.</p><p>Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, GLB, Sarbanes-Oxley, PCI DSS and others.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_10";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_11";s:1781:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services: &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_12";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_13";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:0:"";s:6:"des_14";s:0:"";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:0:"";s:6:"des_15";s:0:"";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(39, 37, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-501</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:193:"<p>The purpose is to implement reasonable and appropriate policies and procedures to comply with the standards, implementation specifications and other requirements of impacted regulations.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:263:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to PIPL assets, resources, and/or sensitive data.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:99:"<p>PIPL will ensure the development of all policies and procedures required by the regulations.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:9:"Procedure";s:5:"des_8";s:308:"<p><br />PIPL will ensure the development of all policies and procedures required by the regulations.<br />PIPL will ensure that all members of the workforce, including managers, are trained on PIPL security policies.<br />PIPL will ensure that the policies and procedures are updated on a regular basis.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:99:"<p>PIPL will ensure the development of all policies and procedures required by the regulations.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:239:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:254:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, HITECH and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:1781:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services, &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(40, 38, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-502</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:292:"<p>The purpose is to maintain the policies and procedures implemented to comply with the impacted regulation in written (or electronic) form and if an action, activity or assessment is required to maintain a written (which may be electronic) record of that action, activity or assessment.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:263:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to PIPL assets, resources, and/or sensitive data.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:187:"<p>PIPL will retain the documentation required by the regulation for six (6) years or longer, from the date of its creation or the date when it was last in effect, whichever is later.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:9:"Procedure";s:5:"des_8";s:802:"<p><strong><em>Time Limit</em></strong></p><p>PIPL will retain the documentation required by the regulation for six (6) years or longer from the date of its creation or the date when it was last in effect, whichever is later.</p><p><strong><em>Availability</em></strong></p><p>PIPL will make documentation available to those persons responsible for implementing the procedures to which the documentation pertains.</p><p><strong><em>Updates</em></strong></p><p>PIPL will review the documentation periodically, and update as needed, in response to environmental or operational changes affecting the security of the sensitive information. Additionally, PIPL must review and update its documentation whenever there is a change in the HIPAA Security Rule or related state, federal, or local regulations.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:127:"<p>The Information Security Officer will be responsible for ensuring the implementation of the requirements of this policy.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:239:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:254:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, HITECH and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:14:"<p>Form(s)</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:1781:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services, &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:44:"<p>Initial effective date: March 2, 2013</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(41, 39, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-601</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:158:"<p>The purpose is to address information classification categories, acceptable access and use of information such as EPHI and other sensitive information.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:269:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to PIPL assets, resources, and/or sensitive data.&nbsp;</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:95:"<p>PIPL will classify information as appropriate and according to its level of sensitivity.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:9:"Procedure";s:5:"des_8";s:1564:"<p>All PIPL information will be organized into two main classes.&nbsp; These classes are &ldquo;Public&rdquo; and &ldquo;Confidential.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p><p>Public information is information that can be shared freely with anyone inside or outside of the organization without the possibility of negative consequences.&nbsp; Public information includes, but is not necessarily limited to:</p><ul><li>General information about PIPL such as the mission statement</li><li>Most marketing information</li></ul><p>Confidential information includes all other information, such as sensitive information, (information that, when shared or disclosed, could possibly have a negative consequence). It is understood that there are varying levels of sensitive information, and the lengths employees should go to protect the information depends on the sensitivity.</p><p>PIPL will rely on the professional judgment of the individual on a daily basis when using and disclosing confidential information. If an individual is unsure of the relative sensitivity of a piece of information, they could contact their supervisor or the Information Security Officer.&nbsp;</p><p>Confidential information includes, but is not necessarily limited to:</p><ul><li>Patient information</li><li>Business information</li><li>Financial information</li><li>Operational information</li><li>Most personnel information</li></ul><p>If the sensitivity of the information is not readily apparent, the creator of the document may mark the document as &ldquo;PIPL Confidential&rdquo; in a prominent location.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:351:"<p>All workforce members are responsible for understanding and following all security related policies and procedures related to Information Classification.</p><p>The Information Security Officer is responsible for ensuring all workforce members understand and follow security related policies and procedures related to Information Classification.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:239:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:254:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, HITECH and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:1781:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services, &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(42, 40, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-602</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:313:"<p>The purpose of this policy is to establish standards for secure communication devices and data on equipment that is owned and/or operated by PIPL. By securing PIPL&rsquo;s network and infrastructure, PIPL will minimize unauthorized access to the organization&rsquo;s proprietary information and technology.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:263:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to PIPL assets, resources, and/or sensitive data.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:318:"<p>PIPL will evaluate the need for secure communication on all networks, public and private, that are utilized to transmit PIPL sensitive information.</p><p>Where secure communications are required, technology and processes will be put in place to ensure the confidentiality and integrity of sensitive information.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:14:"Procedure(s): ";s:5:"des_8";s:690:"<p>Where secure communications are required, technology and processes will be put in place to ensure the confidentiality and integrity of sensitive information.</p><p>The standard for network protocols in the PIPL infrastructure is TCP/IP.</p><p>PIPL will:</p><ul><li>Use encryption as much as possible to protect data</li><li>Use firewall(s) to secure critical segments</li><li>Deploy Intrusion Detection Systems (IDS) and Intrusion Prevention Systems (IPS) on all critical segments</li><li>Disable all services that are not in use or services that have use of which you are not sure</li><li>Use wrappers around all services to log their usage as well as to restrict connectivity</li></ul>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:120:"<p>The Information Security Officer will be responsible for ensuring that network protocols are configured securely.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:239:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:254:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, HITECH and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:1781:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services, &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(43, 41, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-603</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:146:"<p>The purpose of this policy is to protect the confidentiality and integrity of sensitive information that may be sent or received via email.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:432:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to PIPL assets, resources, and/or sensitive data.</p><p>This policy also applies to all systems, networks, and applications, as well as all facilities, which process, store, maintain, or transmit sensitive information.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:184:"<p>PIPL will identify whether sensitive information is permitted to be transmitted over email, and secure all email transmissions of sensitive information whenever it is permitted.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:13:"Procedure(s):";s:5:"des_8";s:5642:"<p>PIPL recognizes that using email without the use of an encryption mechanism is an insecure means of sending and receiving messages. PIPL will evaluate emerging encryption solutions for email and implement them when one is found that is:</p><ul><li>Technically sound;</li><li>Reasonable to implement and use by workforce members, and</li><li>Financially reasonable.</li></ul><p><strong>Guidelines for Sending Sensitive Information via Email</strong></p><p>Until a workable encryption mechanism is implemented, PIPL will utilize the following guidelines regarding sending sensitive information via email:</p><ol><li>Emails containing sensitive information are permitted only when both the sender and receiver are members of PIPL&rsquo;s workforce and the email stays within the confines of PIPL&rsquo;s local network. That is, both email addresses must end with &ldquo;PIPL.com<a id="_anchor_1" href="#_msocom_1" name="_msoanchor_1">[NK1]</a>&nbsp;.&rdquo;</li><li>When sending sensitive information via email, care should be taken to send only the minimum necessary.</li><li>Electronic information about a patient, in an organized set of records, should be protected to the extent that a hard copy record is protected, and disclosed only when required for authorized purposes.</li></ol><p><strong>General Email Requirements</strong></p><ol><li>PIPL email systems are intended for official and authorized purposes only.</li><li>PIPL considers email messages to be company property. Therefore, email equipment operated by or for PIPL staff are subject to the same restrictions on their use as any other company-furnished resource provided for use by members of the workforce.</li><li>Employees must use the PIPL email system for all official email correspondence.</li><li>Employees should have no expectation of privacy in the use of the email system.</li></ol><p><strong>General Guidance about Email</strong></p><p>Every email transmitted by an individual reflects on the organization&rsquo;s credibility and the professionalism of the writer. Adherence to the basic rules of PIPL &ldquo;netiquette&rdquo; below will alleviate problems and help cast you and PIPL in a favorable light.</p><ol><li>Beware of hidden readers. If confidentiality is an issue, do not use email. You may intend to send a message to one person, but an inaccurate keystroke could land the email on dozens or hundreds of readers&rsquo; screens.</li><li>Write as though mom were reading. Do not take email too casually. Write your message as if your Director, the media or your mom were reading it.</li><li>Keep all the organization&rsquo;s policies in mind. A policy is a policy. You are obligated to adhere to the organization&rsquo;s policies, whether working on PIPL provided tools or off site on personal tools.</li><li>Do not take the chance of sending a hastily written email that could worsen an already difficult decision.</li><li>Control the urge to flame. An email flame is a message that is hostile, blunt, rude, insensitive, or obscene.&nbsp; Flames and the obscene and abusive language that feed them have no place at PIPL.</li><li>Respect others&rsquo; time. Do not use the organizational system to send or forward spam, non-business related messages, or personal correspondence.</li><li>Never reply to spam. If you are on the receiving end of spam, do not reply to the &ldquo;unsubscribe&rdquo; option. Your reply merely confirms your email address and encourages the sender to sell your address to other spammers.</li><li>Do not post your business email address on a personal website. Spambots automatically search the web for email addresses for use by spammers.</li><li>Do not email to the world. Send emails only to readers with a legitimate need for the information. Mail to group list only when it is appropriate for everyone on the list to receive the message. Staff is prohibited from sending organizational-wide email messages to all staff without prior approval of the individual&rsquo;s Director, and/or IT. If you do not wish a message to be forwarded once received, put that in the email so the recipient is aware.</li><li>Copy with care. Sending a courtesy copy (CC) or blind courtesy copy (BCC) to a recipient who does not need to read your message wastes everyone&rsquo;s time.</li><li>Do not oversell your message. Reserve the urgent classification for messages that demand immediate attention.</li><li>Ask permission to forward material. Avoid infringement on copyright laws on publications to which you may subscribe. Seek authorization from the original sender before sending out material.</li><li>Consider email limitations. Email may be the best way to deliver a message quickly but is not necessarily the best route to a quick reply. For an immediate response to a pressing issue don&rsquo;t rely on email. Instead, pick up the phone or schedule a face-to-face meeting.</li><li>Know who sees your message. Remember that when you post something on a friend&rsquo;s Facebook page, you are sending it to all of their friends as well. There are few-to-no boundaries in this type of activity.</li></ol><p><strong>Authorized Access to Email Messages</strong></p><p>Email system administrators and others with special system-level access privileges are prohibited from reading electronic messages of others unless authorized by appropriate PIPL management officials. However, PIPL officials will have access to email messages whenever there is a legitimate purpose for such access, e.g., technical or administrative problems.</p><p>When email is not in use, users are to exit the software to prevent unauthorized access.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:545:"<p>All individuals identified in the scope of this policy are responsible for abiding by the terms and guidelines set forth by this policy.</p><p>The Information Security Officer is responsible for:</p><ul><li>Evaluating, on a periodic basis, emerging encryption solutions for email and implementing them when one is found the meets the criteria described in the policy section of this document.</li><li>Maintaining procedures and forms in support of this policy.</li><li>Monitoring and enforcing workforce compliance with this policy.</li></ul>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:336:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention. Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:254:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, HITECH and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:1781:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services, &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(44, 42, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-604</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:209:"<p>The purpose is to implement security measures sufficient to reduce risks and vulnerabilities of remote access connections to PIPL&rsquo;s enterprise infrastructure to a reasonable and appropriate level.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:432:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to PIPL assets, resources, and/or sensitive data.</p><p>Remote access implementations that are covered by this policy include, but are not limited to, dial-in modems, frame relay, ISDN, DSL, VPN, SSH, and cable modems.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:147:"<p>PIPL will take all reasonable and appropriate steps to ensure the secure and authorized use of all remote access capabilities and solutions.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:13:"Procedure(s):";s:5:"des_8";s:2618:"<p>The PIPL remote access infrastructure must follow these guidelines:</p><ol><li>It is the responsibility of PIPL employees, contractors, vendors and agents with remote access privileges to PIPL corporate network to ensure that their remote access connection is given the same consideration as the user&rsquo;s on-site connection to PIPL.</li><li>General access to the Internet for recreational use by immediate household members through the PIPL network on personal computers is permitted for employees that have flat-rate services.<ol><li>The PIPL employee is responsible to ensure the family member does not violate any PIPL policies, does not perform illegal activities, and does not use the access for outside business interests.</li><li>The PIPL employee bears responsibility for the consequences should he or she misuse the access.</li></ol></li><li>Secure remote access must be strictly controlled. Control will be enforced by using strong passwords. Please refer to ECP-218, Password Management Policy.</li><li>At no time should any PIPL employee provide their login or email password to anyone, not even family members.</li><li>PIPL employees and contractors with remote access privileges must ensure that their PIPL-owned or personal computer or workstation, which is remotely connected to PIPL corporate network, is not connected to any other network at the same time, with the exception of personal networks that are under the complete control of the user.</li><li>PIPL employees and contractors with remote access privileges to PIPL&#39;s corporate network must not use non-PIPL email accounts (for example, Hotmail, Yahoo, AOL), or other external resources to conduct PIPL business, thereby ensuring that official business is never confused with personal business.</li><li>Routers for dedicated ISDN lines configured for access to the PIPL network must meet minimum authentication requirements of CHAP.</li><li>Reconfiguration of a home user&#39;s equipment for the purpose of split-tunneling or dual homing is not permitted at any time.</li><li>Frame Relay must meet minimum authentication requirements of DLCI standards.</li><li>Non-standard hardware configurations must be approved by the Information Security Officer.</li><li>All hosts that are connected to PIPL internal networks via remote access technologies must use the most up-to-date anti-virus software. This includes personal computers.</li><li>Organizations or individuals who wish to implement non-standard Remote Access solutions to the PIPL production network must obtain prior approval from the Information Security Officer.</li></ol>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:319:"<p>The Information Security Officer is responsible for:</p><ul><li>Ensuring that all remote access connections are used in accordance with policy requirements;</li><li>Reviewing related log files from key systems on a regular basis, and</li><li>Sending reminders to all employees about remote access security.</li></ul>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:239:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:254:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, HITECH and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:1775:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services, http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0);
