(45, 43, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-605</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:93:"<p>The purpose is to secure the use of portable devices used by members of the workforce.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:484:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to PIPL assets, resources, and/or sensitive data.</p><p>The policy applies to all types of portable devices, including and not limited to laptops, notebooks, PDAs, smartphones, and any other mobile device that is capable to storing or transmitting sensitive information.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:320:"<p>PIPL will ensure that wherever and whenever the use of portable devices is deemed necessary, these devices will be appropriately secured and used only by properly authorized members of the workforce.</p><p>PIPL will ensure that all portable devices will be used according to the guidelines defined in this policy.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:13:"Procedure(s):";s:5:"des_8";s:1555:"<p>Confidential or sensitive data must be accessed only on server systems.</p><p>Sensitive information may only be stored on portable systems if appropriate encryption software authorized by the IT department is installed on the device.</p><p>Any information stored on the portable system must be saved only in those folders that keep information encrypted.</p><p>Strong password controls must be implemented for all users of portable devices. This includes requirements for minimal password length and frequency of password changes.&nbsp; Please refer to ECP-218, Password Management Policy.</p><p>When working on portable devices from a remote location, including from home, only secure connections must be used to access sensitive information. If wireless communication is used with portable devices, then the device must be configured as defined by the IT department to ensure use of secure protocols.&nbsp; Please refer to ECP-604, Remote Access Policy.</p><p>Backups of information from portable devices must be conducted regularly and stored securely.</p><p>Employees must logoff and shut down portable devices with sensitive data before leaving the work space.</p><p>Protection against malicious software should be installed and be kept up to date on portable devices.</p><p>Devices must be configured to automatically logoff users according to ECP-404, Automatic Logoff Policy.</p><p>Portable devices must not be left unattended. When not in use, portable devices should be locked away or special locks should be used to secure the equipment.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:738:"<p>Members of the workforce are responsible for:</p><ul><li>The security of portable devices they use for work</li><li>Taking special care to ensure that sensitive information is not compromised</li></ul><p>The Information Security Officer is responsible for:</p><ul><li>Ensuring that key elements of this policy are included in annual training provided to all members of the workforce.</li><li>Including elements of this policy as security reminders sent to members of the workforce.</li><li>Training members of the workforce on any encryption software or password controls that are installed or implemented on portable devices.</li><li>Conducting random audits of portable systems to check for unauthorized or unsecured files.</li></ul>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:239:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:254:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, HITECH and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:1781:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services, &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(46, 44, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-606</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:192:"<p>The purpose of this policy is to implement security measures sufficient to reduce the risks and vulnerabilities of PIPL&rsquo;s VPN infrastructure to a reasonable and appropriate level.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:263:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to PIPL assets, resources, and/or sensitive data.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:130:"<p>PIPL will ensure the VPN is appropriately secured at all times, and will adhere to the requirements defined in this policy.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:13:"Procedure(s):";s:5:"des_8";s:1821:"<p>PIPL VPN infrastructure must comply with the following guidelines and the guidelines contained within ECP-604, Remote Access Policy:</p><ol><li>Members of the workforce with VPN privileges must ensure that unauthorized users are not allowed access to PIPL internal networks.</li><li>VPN use is to be controlled using either a one-time password authentication such as a token device or a strong password solution.</li><li>When actively connected to the corporate network, VPNs will force all traffic to and from the PC over the VPN tunnel; all other traffic must be dropped.</li><li>Dual (split) tunneling is NOT permitted; only one network connection is allowed.</li><li>VPN gateways will be set up and managed by PIPL network operational groups.</li><li>All computers connected to PIPL internal networks via VPN or any other technology must use the most up-to-date anti-virus software that is the corporate standard (provide URL to this software); this includes personal computers.</li><li>VPN users are automatically disconnected from PIPL network after fifteen minutes of inactivity. The user must then logon again to reconnect to the network. Pings or other artificial network processes are not to be used to keep the connection open.</li><li>The VPN concentrator is limited to an absolute connection time of 24 hours.</li><li>Users of non-PIPL-owned equipment must configure the equipment to comply with PIPL VPN and other policies.</li><li>Only approved VPN clients may be used.</li><li>By using VPN technology with personal equipment, users must understand that their machines are a de facto extension of PIPL network, and as such are subject to the same rules and regulations that apply to PIPL-owned equipment; in other words, their machines must be configured to comply with PIPL Security Policies.</li></ol>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:299:"<p>The Information Security Officer is responsible for:</p><ul><li>Ensuring that all VPN end systems, such as laptops and desktops, are deployed and used based on policy requirements</li><li>Reviewing log files from VPN devices, such as concentrators and other systems, on a regular basis.</li></ul>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:239:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:254:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, HITECH and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:1780:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services, &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:208:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India.<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(47, 45, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-607</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:178:"<p>The purpose is to implement security measures sufficient to reduce risks and vulnerabilities of PIPL&rsquo;s wireless infrastructure to a reasonable and appropriate level.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:263:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to PIPL assets, resources, and/or sensitive data.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:328:"<p>PIPL will operate all wireless networks in a secure manner so as to ensure the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of all sensitive information transmitted over wireless networks.</p><p>PIPL will ensure that all wireless devices are configured and operated according to the requirements set forth in this policy.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:13:"Procedure(s):";s:5:"des_8";s:1555:"<p>PIPL wireless infrastructure must comply with the following guidelines:</p><p><strong><em>Design</em></strong></p><ol><li>Configure a firewall between the wireless network and the wired infrastructure.</li><li>Ensure that 128-bit or higher encryption is used for all wireless communication.</li><li>Fully test and deploy software patches and updates on a regular basis.</li><li>Deploy Intrusion Detection Systems (IDS) on the wireless network to report suspected activities.</li></ol><p><strong><em>Access Points (AP)</em></strong></p><ol><li>Maintain and update an inventory of all Access Points (AP) and wireless devices.</li><li>Locate APs on the interior of buildings instead of near exterior walls and windows as appropriate.</li><li>Place APs in secured areas to prevent unauthorized physical access and user manipulation.</li><li>The default settings on APs, such as those for SSIDs, must be changed.</li><li>APs must be restored to the latest security settings when the reset functions are used.</li><li>Ensure that all APs have strong administrative passwords.</li><li>Enable user authentication mechanisms for the management interfaces of the AP.</li><li>Use SNMPv3 and/or SSL/TLS for Web-based management of APs.</li><li>Turn on audit capabilities on AP; review log files on a regular basis.</li></ol><p><strong><em>Mobile Systems</em></strong></p><ol><li>Install anti-virus software on all wireless clients.</li><li>Install personal firewall software on all wireless clients.</li><li>Disable file sharing between wireless clients.</li></ol>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:354:"<p>The Information Security Officer is responsible for:</p><ol><li>Ensuring that all wireless end systems, such as laptops, PDAs, smartphones and APs, are deployed based on policy requirements.</li><li>Reviewing log files from APs and other systems on a regular basis.</li><li>Sending reminders to all employees about wireless network security.</li></ol>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:239:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:254:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, HITECH and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:1781:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services, &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(48, 46, 'a:48:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-609</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:206:"<p>The purpose of this policy is to address the rights and obligations of both owners of a device used for PIPL work and PIPL&rsquo;s rights and obligations to protect and own its data on these devices.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:397:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to PIPL assets, resources, and/or sensitive data.</p><p>The policy applies to all personal mobile computing equipment that is capable to storing or transmitting sensitive information.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:11:"Definitions";s:5:"des_7";s:2390:"<p>Cloud Service: For the purpose of this policy, a cloud service is virtual data storage or other service located on the Internet and usually managed by a third party.</p><p>Personal Computing Device (Device): A device owned by an employee, contractor or other individual; using it to accomplish work for PIPL. A cloud service which stores data is considered a device for the purpose of this policy. Another definition is a device owned by an agent of PIPL used to produce, modify or view PIPL data. A personally owned device may be a home desktop or laptop, a smartphone or tablet, a pager or cell phone.</p><p>Bring Your Own Device (BYOD): A PIPL supported program that allows Employees to use their own personal computing device to accomplish work for PIPL.</p><p>Employee: Anyone using PIPL Information Infrastructure and acting in PIPL&rsquo;s behalf.</p><p>Employee&rsquo;s Personal Data: Any and all data on the device that does not belong to PIPL and any data that is not a work product. This includes but is not limited to:</p><ol><li>Any file not company related.</li><li>Any location or GPS data.</li><li>Any credentials used to access other non-PIPL services particularly social media sites.</li><li>Device PINs and passwords.</li><li>Any contact information.</li><li>Any device logs including web logs and system logs.</li><li>Personal email or personal social media communications.</li><li>Any personally-purchased movies, music, e-books, or applications.</li><li>Any phone conversations, text messages or other communications.</li><li>Any screenshots, input or output of microphones, cameras, keyboards or pointing devices not explicitly shared with PIPL.</li><li>Any publicly published PIPL data that is freely available to the public.</li><li>Any healthcare information for any individual unless that information is a work product.</li><li>Any financial information for any individual unless that information is a work product.</li></ol><p>Work Product: Data produced or accessed in the course of accessing PIPL systems to do PIPL business or is data produced on a Personal Computing Device as part of an individual&#39;s duties as an agent of PIPL.</p><p>Virtual Private Network (VPN): A PIPL network service allowing remote access to information systems and data. The VPN may require specific configurations, patch levels, and antivirus software for certain devices.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_8";s:167:"<p>It is PIPL&rsquo;s policy to protect the integrity of the organization&rsquo;s data and ensure that data remains safe and secure, and under PIPL&rsquo;s control</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:13:"Procedure(s):";s:5:"des_9";s:8072:"<p>The use of a mobile electronic device (smartphones, tablets, PDAs, etc.) in connection with PIPL business is a privilege granted to employees through approval of their management. PIPL reserves the right to revoke these privileges at any time without notice.</p><p><strong><em>Device Requirements and Configuration</em></strong></p><ol><li>IT is responsible for developing procedures for types of permitted devices and configuring those devices. These procedures may include mobile device management solutions.</li><li>Devices used as BYOD must be one of PIPL&rsquo;s standard approved devices. Other devices are not allowed to connect to PIPL&rsquo;s systems/network. Personal smartphones are not permitted to connect to PIPL&rsquo;s infrastructure without documented consent from PIPL IT. Furthermore, PIPL and PIPL IT reserve the right to disable or disconnect some or all services as well as monitor all activity without prior notification.</li><li>Passwords.<ol><li>The device must be configured to include a password.</li><li>The password must be a minimum of six characters, and contain at least one letter or number (except on devices that cannot accept alphanumeric passwords).</li><li>Passwords must be rotated every 90 days.</li><li>The password must not be one of the employee&rsquo;s previous four passwords.</li></ol></li><li>The device must be configured to lock after 10 failed login attempts.</li><li>The device must be configured with an inactivity screen that requires a PIN or password to unlock.</li><li>Devices must be configured to use SSL or other encryption communications.</li><li>If the Employee disposes or replaces (example: upgrade the device) the device, the permanent memory of the device must be wiped. Simple deletion is not enough.</li><li>Security software that can locate or wipe a lost or stolen device must be installed.</li><li>The Employee must not change or disable configuration settings made or dictated by the PIPL IT department.</li><li>Employees are expected to use their device in an ethical manner. Using your device in ways not designed or intended by the manufacturer is not allowed. This includes, but is not limited to &quot;jail breaking&quot; or &ldquo;rooting&rdquo; your device.</li><li>The Employee and PIPL must follow all other administrative policies when a device is connected to PIPL internal networks or when social media or other collaboration solutions are applied.</li><li>Employees&rsquo; devices must contain the following controls:<ol><li>Anti-virus protection must be maintained and updated.</li><li>Patches:<ul><li>Automatic Updates must always be configured and applied.</li><li>Applications must be configured to update automatically when possible.</li><li>Employees must regularly check that applications are updated.</li></ul></li><li>Additional Software and Applications<ul><li>Employees are expected to understand the consequences of installing applications on devices used to access PIPL data.</li><li>If the Employee does not understand the consequences of installing a particular application then they should not do so until they do more investigation into the application.</li><li>Only well-known and well respected application vendors and online repositories should be used. Common repositories by your Internet Service Provider, Operating System, Hardware Vendor or default Market Place should be used.</li><li>PIPL may require applications to be installed on the device. Any software required by PIPL will comply with all PIPL policies, including this one, Federal, State, and local laws.</li></ul></li><li>Root, Administrative and Employee Access and Accounts<ul><li>Employees should not use a local device account with administrator or root rights to access the Internet for devices that support multiple local accounts.</li><li>Employees should use a restricted account on the device for accessing information into PIPL.</li><li>Employees who accesses sensitive PIPL data should not share devices with family members.</li></ul></li><li>PIPL Data<ul><li>Many state and federal laws as well as PIPL policies make the Employee responsible for safeguarding PIPL data in their possession.</li><li>Never keep the only copy or the newest copy of PIPL data on a personal device. This opens the Employee to legal actions including confiscations and searches beyond this policy.</li><li>If PIPL data is created on the device then the only copy or newest copy of PIPL data should be moved to PIPL&rsquo;s network as soon as practical.</li><li>Employees will not publicize PIPL data to online services.&nbsp; PIPL data that Employees purposefully or inadvertently publish on social sites, cloud sites or personal servers is subject to all laws, regulations and PIPL policies and procedures.</li><li>Employees must immediately report lost or stolen devices that have been used to access PIPL data to their supervisor.</li><li>Breaches, disclosures, possible disclosures or malware infections on personally owned devices or cloud services utilized through personally owned devices must be reported to the Employee&rsquo;s supervisor immediately.</li></ul></li></ol></li></ol><p><strong><em>Contents of Security Agreements</em></strong></p><p>Employee:</p><ol><li>Retains absolute ownership of the device and may use it as they see fit.</li><li>Understands that PIPL may inadvertently come in contact with their personal data. If an Employee discovers that PIPL has come in contact with their personal data they should inform their supervisor.</li><li>Agrees that PIPL may obligate them to set or maintain certain configurations and practices before the Employee is allowed access to PIPL data. If the Employee disagrees with any of these requirements, or if the Employee circumvents them, then the Employee must not access or process PIPL data via the device.</li><li>Understands that PIPL might require software be installed on the device if the Employee wishes to access PIPL data.</li><li>Is obligated to remove all PIPL data from personally owned devices upon separation from PIPL or by PIPL&rsquo;s request.</li><li>Agrees that PIPL has the right to manage the device including remote wiping of data including destruction or loss of any and all data on the device. This is including, but not limited to, application installation/removal, configuration setting changes, application/system updates, and resetting the device and may be done without prior notification.</li><li>Upon separation from PIPL or by PIPL request, the Employee must reconcile software licenses purchased by PIPL and installed on personally owned devices. Depending on the licensing of the software and PIPL requests, this might mean an Employee must reimburse PIPL for the software, destroy the software or otherwise release the license. The PIPL may decide to allow the Employee to keep software with no further value.</li></ol><p>PIPL</p><ol><li>Retains absolute ownership of the work product of its agents and has the right and obligation to govern this data.</li><li>Respects the ownership rights of these devices and will never configure, modify, delete, monitor, or install anything on the device, including wiping the device or resetting the device PIN or password unless a business or security reason is required.</li><li>Reserves the right to search a User&rsquo;s device for PIPL&rsquo;s data without the prior consent of the Employee unless required by law.</li><li>May limit what data may be accessed remotely.</li><li>Must permanently delete all its copies or records of personal data discovered from a User&rsquo;s Personal Computing Device and inform the Employee as soon as discovered and practical.</li></ol><p>PIPL and the Employee must comply with all Federal, State and Local laws. In this context the law might require PIPL to access its data as well as your data on your device. The Employee may be compelled to provide any data from their device because of these laws. The Employee understands that because of these laws they are giving up some rights to their device by accessing PIPL data.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:6:"des_10";s:549:"<p>The Information Security Officer is responsible for the implementation of this policy.</p><p>Employee responsibilities: maintain security and integrity of their device and PIPL data as outlined in this policy and related HIPAA security policies.</p><p>The PIPL Responsibilities</p><ol><li>PIPL will not access an Employee&rsquo;s device or data for any reason nor configure any services to do so that does not conform to this policy.</li><li>PIPL may offer security services for lost or stolen devices that wipe or locate these devices.</li></ol>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_11";s:239:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_12";s:254:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, HITECH and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_13";s:25:"<p>Security Agreement</p>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_14";s:1775:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services, http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_15";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";s:11:"subtitle_16";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_16";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_16";s:2:"16";}', '', '', 0),
(49, 47, 'a:48:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-701</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:349:"<p>The purpose is to assist employees of PIPL in defining and identifying potential security breaches of protected information, such as Protected Health Information (PHI), personal information or other confidential information. Through proper education and preparedness, PIPL can better protect all of its confidential and sensitive information.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:263:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to PIPL assets, resources, and/or sensitive data.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:11:"Definitions";s:5:"des_7";s:473:"<p><strong>Breach: </strong>the acquisition, access, use, or disclosure of protected health information in a manner not permitted [by the Privacy Rule] which compromises the security or privacy of the protected health information.</p><p><strong>Unsecured Protected Health Information: </strong>PHI that is not rendered unusable, unreadable, or indecipherable to unauthorized persons through the use of a technology or methodology specified by the Secretary in guidance.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_8";s:90:"<p>PIPL will employ policies, technology, and education to identify security breaches.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:13:"Procedure(s):";s:5:"des_9";s:3203:"<p>A breach shall be treated as discovered by PIPL on the first day the breach is known to PIPL, or by exercising reasonable diligence would have been known to PIPL.</p><p>Breach does not include:</p><p>1. Any unintentional acquisition, access, or use of protected information by an employee or individual acting under the authority of a covered entity or business associate if&nbsp;</p><ul><li>such acquisition, access, or use was made in good faith and within the course and scope of the employment or other professional relationship of such employee or individual, respectively, with the covered entity or business associate; and</li><li>such information is not further acquired, accessed, used, or disclosed by any person; or</li></ul><p>2. Any inadvertent disclosure from an individual who is otherwise authorized to access protected health information at a facility operated by a covered entity or business associate to another similarly situated individual at same facility; and</p><p>3. Any such information received as a result of such disclosure is not further acquired, accessed, used, or disclosed without authorization by any person.</p><p>4. Information that has been rendered unusable, unreadable, or indecipherable.</p><p><strong><em>Policies and Procedures:</em></strong></p><p>PIPL will implement policies and procedures to protect against and identify data breaches. The policies will minimally include:</p><ul><li>ECP-202, Risk Analysis Policy</li><li>ECP-207, Workforce Security Policy</li><li>ECP-219, Security Incident Procedures</li><li>ECP-220, Response and Reporting Policy</li><li>ECP-226, Applications and Data Criticality Policy</li><li>ECP-309, Disposal Policy</li><li>ECP-405, Encryption and Decryption Policy</li><li>ECP-702, Data Breach Management Policy</li><li>ECP-703, Data Breach Notification Policy</li></ul><p><strong><em>Technology:</em></strong></p><p>The technology infrastructure at PIPL will be monitored for data breaches utilizing standard industry technologies including but not limited to the following:</p><ul><li>Firewall</li><li>Intrusion Detection Systems/Intrusion Prevention Systems</li><li>Virus Protection Systems</li><li>Malware Protection Systems</li><li>Event Monitoring Systems</li></ul><p><strong><em>Education:</em></strong></p><p>PIPL business users and IT staff will be educated in standard breach identification and prevention methodologies; including but not limited to the following:</p><ul><li>Suspicious PC activity</li><li>Suspicious emails regarding protected information</li><li>Virus, Malware and Security software alerts</li><li>Phishing methods</li></ul><p>If a breach of sensitive information is discovered the person making the discovery will notify the Information Security Officer immediately.</p><p>The Information Security Officer will, as necessary, execute ECP-219, Security Incident Procedures Policy, ECP-220, Response and Reporting Policy, ECP-702, Data Breach Management Policy, ECP-703, Data Breach Notification Policy, and other policies as appropriate.</p><p>Persons will report any improper disposal of sensitive information to the Information Security Officer, utilizing ECP-309, Disposal Policy as a guide.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:6:"des_10";s:307:"<p>All workforce members are responsible for understanding and following all policies and procedures related to data breach discovery.</p><p>The Information Security Officer is responsible for ensuring all workforce members understand and follow policies and procedures related to data breach discovery.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_11";s:239:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_12";s:282:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, ARRA/HITECH, applicable state laws and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_13";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_14";s:2307:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/</a> February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>NIST 800-111: <a href="http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-111/SP800-111.pdf">http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-111/SP800-111.pdf</a>.</li><li>Code of Federal Regulations: Title 45, Public Welfare: <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/get-cfr.cgi?TITLE=45&amp;PART=160&amp;SECTION=103&amp;TYPE=TEXT">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/get-cfr.cgi?TITLE=45&amp;PART=160&amp;SECTION=103&amp;TYPE=TEXT</a>.</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_15";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";s:11:"subtitle_16";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_16";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_16";s:2:"16";}', '', '', 0);
