(50, 48, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-702</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:299:"<p>The purpose is to provide guidance on decisions made and actions taken following the identification of a data breach. This policy is designed to minimize the loss and destruction of data, mitigate the weakness that was exploited, and restore all computing and other impacted services to PIPL.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:393:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to PIPL assets, resources, and/or sensitive data.&nbsp; More specifically, this policy applies to employees of PIPL that are responsible for the security of protected information.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:224:"<p>PIPL will ensure that if a data breach is discovered the steps laid out in this policy will be followed in order to prevent further damage, assess the severity of the breach, and manage all breach- related activities.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:13:"Procedure(s):";s:5:"des_8";s:3341:"<p>If a data breach is discovered at PIPL, the following steps will be followed in order to prevent further damage, assess the severity of the breach, and manage all associated breach-related activities.</p><ul><li>Once a breach has been identified, according to ECP-701, Data Breach Discovery Policy, the Information Security Officer will:</li><li>Assemble the Security Incident Response Team (SIRT) according to ECP-219, Security Incident Procedures Policy;</li><li>The SIRT will conduct a risk assessment. The assessment will consider at least the following factors:</li></ul><ol><li>the nature and extent of the protected health information involved, including the types of identifiers and the likelihood of re-identification;</li><li>the unauthorized person who used the protected health information or to whom the disclosure was made;</li><li>whether the protected health information was actually acquired or viewed; and</li><li>the extent to which the risk to the protected health information has been mitigated.</li></ol><ul><li>Develop a response according to ECP-220, Response and Reporting Policy;</li><li>Review the breach details and develop an appropriate response to prevent further data leakage, and</li><li>Assess the details of the breach.</li></ul><ul><li>The Information Security Officer and the SIRT will manage all phases of the process once a breach has been identified.</li><li>The Information Security Officer and the SIRT will keep PIPL leadership apprised of the situation.</li><li>Priorities of the Information Security Officer and the SIRT will be:<ol><li>Stopping the data leakage</li><li>Mitigation of the weakness that was exploited</li><li>Restoration of normal business</li><li>Notification of persons and businesses impacted as deemed appropriate</li></ol></li><li>The Information Security Officer and SIRT will work with PIPL legal counsel to determine applicable state and federal laws that may be applicable to the incident; including by not limited to HIPAA, HITECH, and state breach notification laws.</li><li>If any form of protected information, as defined in ECP-701, Data Breach Discovery Policy is at risk then the Information Security Officer and SIRT are to enact ECP-703, Breach Notification Policy.</li><li>Forensic analysis of the breach is to begin immediately upon determination of the breach, unless law enforcement deems a delay is appropriate, or additional forensic support is required beyond the PIPL IT Team.</li><li>All meeting minutes, technical documentation, and hand written notes of the breach are to be compiled by the Information Security Officer or designee within 72 hours of the closure of the breach.</li><li>Any systems that were compromised or targeted as part of an incident resulting in an investigation may be quarantined as determined by the Information Security Officer and SIRT.</li><li>Based upon the scope of the perceived threat the Information Security Officer and SIRT will notify local law enforcement, the FBI Cyber Security Team, or the FBI Internet Crime Complaint Center (IC3).<ul><li>FBI Cyber Security Team: <a href="http://www.fbi.gov/contact/fo/fo.htm">http://www.fbi.gov/contact/fo/fo.htm</a></li><li>FBI Internet Crime Complaint Center (IC3):&nbsp; <a href="http://www.ic3.gov/default.aspx">http://www.ic3.gov/default.aspx</a>.</li></ul></li></ul>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:411:"<p>The Security Incident Response Team (SIRT) is responsible for the proper management of the security incident.</p><p>All workforce members are responsible for understanding and following all policies and procedures related to data breaches.</p><p>The Information Security Officer is responsible for ensuring all workforce members understand and follow policies and procedures related to security breaches.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:239:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:282:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, ARRA/HITECH, applicable state laws and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:2315:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/</a> February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>NIST 800-111: <a href="http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-111/SP800-111.pdf">http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-111/SP800-111.pdf</a>.</li><li>Code of Federal Regulations, Title 45, Public Welfare: <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/get-cfr.cgi?TITLE=45&amp;PART=160&amp;SECTION=103&amp;TYPE=TEXT">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/get-cfr.cgi?TITLE=45&amp;PART=160&amp;SECTION=103&amp;TYPE=TEXT</a>.</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and You&rsquo;re her</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(51, 49, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-703</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:140:"<p>The purpose is to provide guidance on the notification actions required following the discovery of a breach of protected information.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:393:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to PIPL assets, resources, and/or sensitive data.&nbsp; More specifically, this policy applies to employees of PIPL that are responsible for the security of protected information.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:398:"<p>PIPL will notify persons and organizations that have been impacted by a data breach. Breach notification is necessary in all situations except those in which the covered entity or business associate, as applicable, demonstrates, through a risk assessment, that there is a low probability that the PHI has been compromised (or one of the other exceptions to the definition of breach applies).</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:13:"Procedure(s):";s:5:"des_8";s:2848:"<p>PIPL will notify persons and organization that have been impacted by a data breach.</p><ol><li>The Information Security Officer will work with PIPL legal counsel to determine state and federal laws that may be applicable to the incident; including but not limited to HIPAA, HITECH, and state breach notification regulations</li><li>PIPL has the burden of proof for showing why breach notification was not required. Accordingly, PIPL must document why the impermissible use or disclosure falls under one of the exceptions under Section 164.402.</li><li>The Information Security Officer will notify the marketing and communications department of PIPL prior to any public notices</li><li>Notifications will be made in the most expedient time possible and without unreasonable delay</li><li>Notifications are to occur according to the requirements of HITECH Act for breaches of protected health information (no later than 60 calendar days from the discovery of the breach) or applicable state breach laws for protected health information.</li><li>The time period for breach notification begins when the incident is first known, not when the investigation of the incident is complete, even if it is initially unclear whether the incident constitutes a breach as defined in the rule.</li><li>Notifications may be delayed at the request of law enforcement agencies as part of their investigation process</li><li>Notifications may be delayed to determine the scope of the breach and restore the reasonable integrity, security and confidentiality of the impacted systems</li><li>Notifications will be made at no charge to the impacted patients or organizations</li><li>Method(s) of notification may vary according to the type of breach, severity of breach, and applicable laws and regulations therefore;</li><li>All breach notifications will be made according to HITECH standards; unless state regulations set more rigorous requirements. (ARRA &ndash; Sec 13402 &ndash; Notification in the Case of a Breach)<ul><li>HITECH requires covered entities to notify patients whose unsecured information has been breached within 60 days of discovery</li><li>HITECH requires written notification to affected patients by mail and if urgent, by telephone.</li><li>HITECH requires business associates to notify covered entities about breaches.</li><li>HITECH requires a conspicuous posting of the breach on the home page of the covered entity involved as determined by the Secretary of the Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) or in major print or broadcast media</li><li>HITECH requires breaches of over 500 affected patients to be reported to media outlets and the Secretary of HHS.</li><li>HITECH requires breaches of less than 500 affected patients to be submitted as part of an annual breach log to the Secretary of HHS.</li></ul></li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:295:"<p>All workforce members are responsible for understanding and following all policies and procedures related to data breaches.</p><p>The Information Security Officer is responsible for ensuring all workforce members understand and follow all policies and procedures related to data breaches.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:239:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:282:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, ARRA/HITECH, applicable state laws and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:2307:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/</a> February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>NIST 800-111: <a href="http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-111/SP800-111.pdf">http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-111/SP800-111.pdf</a>.</li><li>Code of Federal Regulations, Title 45, Public Welfare: <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/get-cfr.cgi?TITLE=45&amp;PART=160&amp;SECTION=103&amp;TYPE=TEXT">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/get-cfr.cgi?TITLE=45&amp;PART=160&amp;SECTION=103&amp;TYPE=TEXT</a>.</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(52, 50, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-705</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:136:"<p>The purpose is to provide guidance on when and how to notify the impacted patient(s) following a breach of protected information.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:377:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to sensitive information by PIPL.&nbsp; More specifically, this policy applies to employees of PIPL that are responsible for the security of protected information.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:237:"<p>PIPL will notify persons that have been impacted by a data breach in accordance with the ECP-703, Data Breach Notification Policy.</p><p>This policy will assist in determining if, when and how impacted patients are to be notified.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:13:"Procedure(s):";s:5:"des_8";s:4489:"<p>PIPL will notify persons who have been impacted by a data breach, in accordance with the ECP-703, Data Breach Notification Policy.</p><p><strong>The following steps will be taken to notify impacted patients following a breach of protected information:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>How soon to notify:</strong></li></ul><p>PIPL will notify impacted patients within 60 days of the discovery of the breach, or sooner if required by state regulation.&nbsp;</p><ul><li><strong>Who will notify:</strong></li></ul><p>The Information Security Officer will work with the Security Incident Response Team (SIRT), PIPL legal team, Office of the CEO and the marketing team to develop and coordinate all communications.</p><p><strong>Methods of Notification</strong></p><ul><li>Letter via first class mail or email if specified as preferred by the individual, to individuals last known address:<ul><li>See Attachment A &ndash; Sample Letter to Patients</li></ul></li><li>If patient is deceased then the above applies to their next of kin or personal representative.</li><li>Multiple notifications may be necessary as information becomes available.</li><li>If PIPL does not have sufficient contact information for some or all of the affected individuals, or if some notices are returned as undeliverable, requires a covered entity to provide substitute notice for the unreachable individuals.</li><li>The substitute form of notice should be reasonably calculated to reach the individuals for whom it is being provided.</li><li>If there are fewer than 10 individuals for whom PIPL has insufficient or out-of-date contact information to provide the written notice, PIPL will provide substitute notice to such individuals through an alternative form of written notice, by telephone, or other means.</li><li>If PIPL has insufficient or out-of-date contact information for 10 or more individuals, PIPL will provide substitute notice through either a conspicuous posting for a period of 90 days on the home page of its web site or conspicuous notice in major print or broadcast media in geographic areas where the individuals affected by the breach likely reside.</li><li>For either method involving 10 or more individuals, PIPL is also required to have a toll-free phone number, active for 90 days, where an individual can learn whether the individual&rsquo;s unsecured protected health information may be included in the breach and to include the number in the notice.</li><li>PIPL with out-of-date or insufficient contact information for some individuals can attempt to update the contact information so that they can provide direct written notification, in order to limit the number of individuals for whom substitute notice is required.</li><li>Where the individual affected by a breach is a minor or otherwise lacks legal capacity due to a physical or mental condition, notice to the parent or other person who is the personal representative of the individual would satisfy the requirements.</li><li>In the limited circumstances in which an individual has agreed only to receive communications from PIPL orally or by telephone, PIPL is permitted under the Rule to telephone the individual to request and have the individual pick up their written breach notice from PIPL directly.<ul><li>In cases in which the individual does not agree or wish to travel to PIPL to pick up the written breach notice, PIPL should provide all of the information in the breach notice over the phone to the individual, and document that it has done so.</li></ul></li></ul><p><strong>All notifications to Individuals must contain the following items:</strong></p><ul><li>A brief description of what happened, including the date of the breach and the date of the discovery of the breach, if known.</li><li>A description of the types of unsecured protected health information that were involved in the breach (such as whether full name, social security number, date of birth, home address, account number, disability code, or other types of information were involved).</li><li>Any steps patients should take to protect themselves from potential harm resulting from the breach.</li><li>A brief description of what PIPL involved is doing to investigate the breach, to mitigate losses, and to protect against any further breaches.</li><li>Contact procedures for individuals to ask questions or learn additional information, which shall include a toll-free telephone number, an email address, Web site, or postal address.</li></ul>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:347:"<p>All workforce members who are involved in the breach notification process are responsible for understanding and following all policies and procedures related to data breaches.</p><p>The Information Security Officer is responsible for ensuring all workforce members understand and follow all policies and procedures related to data breaches.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:239:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:282:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, ARRA/HITECH, applicable state laws and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:53:"<p>Attachment A &ndash; Sample Letter to Patients</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:2493:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/</a> February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>NIST 800-111: <a href="http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-111/SP800-111.pdf">http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-111/SP800-111.pdf</a>.</li><li>Code of Federal Regulations, Title 45, Public Welfare: <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/get-cfr.cgi?TITLE=45&amp;PART=160&amp;SECTION=103&amp;TYPE=TEXT">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/get-cfr.cgi?TITLE=45&amp;PART=160&amp;SECTION=103&amp;TYPE=TEXT</a>.</li><li>Department of Health and Human Services: <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/office/about/rgn-hqaddresses.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/office/about/rgn-hqaddresses.html</a>.</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and You&rsquo;re her</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(53, 51, 'a:48:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-707</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:10:"Background";s:5:"des_5";s:854:"<p>PIPL recognizes that the use of the internet has many benefits for PIPL and its staff. The internet and email make communication more efficient and effective. Therefore, staff is encouraged to use the internet and email appropriately.</p><p>Today, social media encompasses a broad range of online activity, all of which is track-able and traceable.&nbsp; Social media networks include, but are not limited to:</p><ul><li>Blogs;</li><li>Social networks, such as Facebook and MySpace;</li><li>Professional networks, such as LinkedIn;</li><li>Live blogging tools, such as Twitter;</li><li>Photo- and video-sharing sites, such as Flickr, Pinterest, and YouTube, and</li><li>Social bookmarking tools, such as Digg and Delicious.</li></ul><p>New online tools and technical advances introduce new opportunities to build a &ldquo;virtual&rdquo; footprint.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_6";s:349:"<p>The purpose is to ensure staff members who use social media, either as part of their job or in a personal capacity, understand the organization&rsquo;s expectations for social media engagements concerning PIPL, its services, PIPL staff, PIPL&rsquo;s patients, its competitors, its vendors and/or business-related individuals or organizations.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_7";s:263:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to PIPL assets, resources, and/or sensitive data.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:13:"Procedure(s):";s:5:"des_8";s:4928:"<p><strong><em>Internet Posts (examples: blog posts, social media posts)</em></strong></p><ul><li>Do not presume that your activities on the internet are private or your business alone. Outside the workplace, your rights to privacy and free speech protect online activity conducted on your personal social networks with your personal email address. However, what you publish on such personal online sites should never be attributed to PIPL and should not appear to be endorsed by or originated by PIPL.&nbsp; This means, whether working on PIPL equipment during business hours, or on personal technology tools at home after work, posting text, photos, or videos about the organization, PIPL staff, PIPL patients, products or services, etc., without express permission from your Director may be considered a violation of this policy.</li><li>If you choose to list your work affiliation on a social network, then you should regard all communications on that network as you would in a professional network.&nbsp; Online lives are ultimately linked, whether or not you choose to mention PIPL in your personal online networking activity.</li><li>You are responsible for what you post. You are personally responsible for any of your online activity conducted with the PIPL email address, and/or which can be traced back to the organization&rsquo;s domain, and/or activity which uses organization assets. The PIPL.com [organization&rsquo;s website] address attached to your name implies that you are acting on the organization&rsquo;s behalf.</li><li>While utilizing PIPL-provided tools, disclose that you are employed by PIPL, be clear about what department or service you are representing and what are your roles and accountabilities.</li><li>Personal blogs should display a clear disclaimer that the views expressed by the author in the blog are the author&rsquo;s alone and do not represent the views of PIPL.&nbsp; Make it clear in your post that you are speaking for <em>yourself</em> and <strong>not </strong>on behalf of the organization.</li><li>Write what you know, write in the first person and make sure you write and post about your areas of expertise, especially as it relates to PIPL.&nbsp;</li><li>You may not disclose any confidential or proprietary information about PIPL, its patients, affiliates, vendors, or suppliers.</li><li>Do not use or disclose any patient identifiable information, or any patient scenarios of any kind on any social media.</li><li>PIPL logos may not be utilized without written consent. Contact Marketing to obtain written consent.</li><li>While you are at work, please refrain from online activities that do not bring value to PIPL. Think of your personal time online as you think of personal phone calls or emails. If not required for your particular job role/activity, online activities should be limited to non-work time. &ldquo;Non-work time&rdquo; is defined as before a shift begins, during breaks or meal periods, or after a shift ends. Social media activities should not interfere with work commitments.</li><li>Remember that the internet is not anonymous, nor does it forget. Everything written on the web can be very easily traced back to its author. Information is backed up often; posts in one forum are usually replicated in others through tracebacks, reposts, or references.</li><li>If it gives you pause, pause. If you are about to send an email or post a blog, for example, and the message makes you even the slightest bit uncomfortable, do not shrug it off and hit &ldquo;send.&rdquo; Take a minute to review these guidelines, figure out what may be bothering you, and revise the content.</li></ul><p><strong>&nbsp;<em>Property Rights and Confidentiality</em></strong></p><ul><li>All information created, transmitted, acquired, downloaded, or uploaded via the organization&rsquo;s network and internet or intranet is the property of PIPL.</li><li>Internal and external email messages are considered business records and may be subject to discovery in the event of litigation. All electronic communications produced through the utilization of PIPL tools or internet access, including internal and external emails, may be subject to disclosure to a third party.</li><li>Email is not guaranteed to be private or confidential. All electronic communications are PIPL&rsquo;s property. Therefore, PIPL reserves the right at any time to examine, monitor, and regulate email messages, directories and files, as well as internet usage.</li></ul><p>For additional information related to social media policies and practices, workforce members should review the following policies:</p><ul><li>ECP-306, Workstation Use Policy;</li><li>ECP-603, Email Security Policy;</li><li>ECP-604, Remote Access Policy;</li><li>ECP-605, Portable Devices Policy;</li><li>ECP-606, VPN Policy;</li><li>ECP-708, Cell Phone and Smartphone Policy, and</li><li>ECP-709, Secure Text Message Policy.</li></ul>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_9";s:821:"<p>PIPL and its workforce members will maintain effective electronic communications that are consistent with the PIPL&rsquo;s beliefs and workforce standards. The guidelines contained within this policy apply whether or not you are using PIPL tools to IM, text or email, or whether you are using the Internet as part of your job or for personal social networking that involves PIPL references.</p><p>This policy is based on PIPL&rsquo;s &ldquo;3 Rs of Electronic Engagement&rdquo;:</p><ul><li>Be clear about whom you are <strong>Representing</strong>.</li><li>Take <strong>Responsibility </strong>for ensuring that any references to PIPL are factually correct and do not breach confidentiality requirements.</li><li>Show <strong>Respect</strong> for the individuals and communities with whom/which you interact.</li></ul>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:6:"des_10";s:801:"<p>All individuals, groups, and organizations identified in the scope of this policy are responsible for ensuring compliance with this policy. Further, all workforce members are obligated to report suspected violations of this policy to their Director, PIPL Compliance Officer, IT or Human Resources.</p><p>The Information Security Officer is responsible for ensuring all workforce members understand and follow this policy and associated controls.</p><p>If an activity by an individual is seen as in conflict with the content and intent of this policy the Department Director, upon investigation and confirmation of such conflict, will evaluate options including cessation of the identified activity, loss of internet availability or initiating the Sanction Policy, up to and including dismissal.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_11";s:239:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_12";s:254:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, HITECH and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_13";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_14";s:1781:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services, &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_15";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";s:11:"subtitle_16";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_16";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_16";s:2:"16";}', '', '', 0),
(54, 52, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-708</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:240:"<p>The purpose is to provide reasonable and appropriate safeguards to ensure the confidentiality, integrity, and availability (CIA) of information assets by protecting assets such as cell phones and smartphones from unauthorized access.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:394:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to PIPL assets, resources, and/or sensitive data and anyone else granted access to access sensitive information such as EPHI on devices such as cell phones and smartphones by PIPL.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:394:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to PIPL assets, resources, and/or sensitive data and anyone else granted access to access sensitive information such as EPHI on devices such as cell phones and smartphones by PIPL.</p>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:13:"Procedure(s):";s:5:"des_8";s:3344:"<p><strong><em>General Guidance</em></strong></p><ol><li>Staff may use cell phones to communicate during non-work hours (before or after shifts, during breaks or meal periods) and during emergencies.</li><li>Cell phone conversations should not occur in any area where patients or visitors are present.</li><li>Cell phones should be turned off or set to silent or vibrate mode during meetings, conferences and in other locations where incoming calls may disrupt normal workflow.</li><li>Directors reserve the right to request that an individual provide his/her cell phone bills and usage reports for calls made during the working hours of the person to determine if use is excessive.</li><li>Remember confidentiality when using cell phones within the organization. An overheard cell phone conversation or an indiscreet text message could put the organization at risk.</li></ol><p><strong><em>Confidential Information</em></strong></p><ol><li>All cell phone/smartphone users must hold sensitive information such as EPHI in confidence and in accordance with the HIPAA Privacy Rule, HIPAA Security Rule, the HITECH Act, as well as the terms of the Employee Confidentiality Agreement, and all PIPL policies and procedures.</li><li>Protected EPHI and other confidential information may only be read, taken, used, copied or discussed in conjunction with the direct performance of the users&#39; duties.&nbsp;</li><li>Any violation of this policy or unauthorized use or disclosure of patient information will result in PIPL taking appropriate HR and/or legal action against the user. <a name="_Toc100459597"></a><a name="_Toc393034467"></a><a name="_Toc350164606"></a></li></ol><p><strong><em>Security of the Equipment</em></strong></p><ol><li>Portable devices such as cell phones and smartphones must not be left unattended in public locations.</li><li>Upon request at any time, an employee will be responsible for returning all portable devices (e.g. PIPL provided cell phones, smartphones) and media.</li><li>Devices requiring repair are to be returned to the IT Help Desk on a timely basis. An employee must never attempt to repair any device or authorize repairs by any third party.</li><li>Stolen or misplaced portable devices must be reported immediately to the IT Help Desk. All passwords will immediately be changed to prevent unauthorized access.<a name="_Toc100459598"></a><a name="_Toc393034468"></a><a name="_Toc350164607"></a></li></ol><p><strong><em>Security of Data</em></strong></p><ol><li>It is the responsibility of the employee to adhere to all PIPL policies and procedures regarding the appropriate access, use, storage and disposal of EPHI on devices such as cell phones, smartphones and others.</li><li>Regular backups must be performed on portable devices to ensure information is protected from device failure. Questions regarding appropriate backup processes and technology should be forwarded to the IT Help Desk.</li><li>It is the employee&rsquo;s responsibility to ensure that the media used to back up a portable device such as cell phones or smartphones is secured, protected and disposed of according to established policies.</li><li>EPHI residing on a portable device must be encrypted and password-protected where appropriate.</li><li>All information present on a mobile device shall be the property of PIPL.</li></ol>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:263:"<p>The Information Security Officer is responsible for the implementation of this policy and associated controls.</p><p>All individuals, groups, and organizations identified in the scope of this policy are responsible for ensuring compliance with this policy.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:239:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:254:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, HITECH and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:1781:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>International Standards Organization (ISO 27002).</li><li>HIPAA Final Security Rule, 45 CFR Parts 160, 162, and 164, Department of Health and Human Services, &nbsp;http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/securityrule/, February 20, 2003.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0);
