(55, 53, 'a:45:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:14:"<p>ECP-800</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.0</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 15, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:244:"<p>To ensure that PIPL establishes configuration standards, installs and maintains firewall configurations, and restricts connections between untrusted networks and networks/systems containing, or providing access to, sensitive information.</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:263:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, temporary workers, and anyone else granted access to PIPL assets, resources, and/or sensitive data.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:7901:"<p>PIPL installs and maintains a firewall configuration to protect sensitive information and establishes firewall configuration standards.</p><p>All PIPL systems must be protected from unauthorized access from untrusted networks, whether entering the system via the Internet as e-commerce, employees&rsquo; Internet access through desktop browsers, employees&rsquo; email access, dedicated connections such as business-to-business connections, via wireless networks, or via other sources. Often, seemingly insignificant paths to and from untrusted networks can provide unprotected pathways into key systems.</p><p>PIPL understands that firewalls are a key protection mechanism for any computer network. As such, proper configuration and deployment is a must.</p><ul><li>PIPL deploys a firewall system.</li></ul><p>PIPL establishes firewall configuration standards that include the following:</p><ul><li><strong>Demilitarized Zone (DMZ)</strong>. A firewall is required at each Internet connection and between any DMZ and the internal network zone.<ul><li>PIPL implements a firewall on every connection coming into and out of the PIPL network. This allows the organization to monitor and control access in and out, and to minimize the chances of a malicious individuals obtaining access to the internal network or information from the network traffic.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Roles and Responsibilities</strong>. PIPL creates a description of groups, roles, and responsibilities for logical management of network components. Additionally, PIPL ensures that someone is assigned to be responsible for the security of all components and no devices are left unmanaged. This individual is aware of their responsibility.</li><li><strong>Change Control</strong>. All changes to firewall configurations and rules must go through PIPL&rsquo;s Change Control process. This is to ensure that changes do not negatively impact business processes or functions or introduce new security risks/vulnerabilities. Additionally this helps to ensure that new rules have a valid business justification.</li><li><strong>Software Updates</strong>. All firewalls must run the most current version of software supported. This helps to ensure that the devices are not susceptible to known vulnerabilities. All software updates that patch security vulnerabilities will be applied within 30 days of release from the vendor.</li><li><strong>Logging</strong>. A minimum level of activity logging will be configured on all firewalls. Logging of connections through the firewall, as appropriate, will be configured to assist in troubleshooting or security investigations. At a minimum actions logged must include:<ul><li>Successful and failed connection/login attempts to management interfaces</li><li>Elevation of privileges</li><li>Administrative actions</li><li>Configuration/rule changes</li></ul></li><li><strong>Documentation</strong>. PIPL maintains documentation and business justification for use of all services, protocols, and ports allowed. The documentation includes the security features implemented for those protocols considered to be insecure.<ul><li>PIPL clearly documents the decisions to open services, protocols, and ports, ensuring that all other services, protocols, and ports are disabled or removed.</li><li>There may be times when PIPL identifies commonly-attacked or insecure services, protocols, or ports that are necessary for current business needs. PIPL&rsquo;s senior management and ISO will clearly understand and document the risk exposed by use of these services, protocols or ports. If necessary to use, these services, protocols or ports business justification shall be documented along with any security features that allow these protocols to be used securely</li><li>If these insecure services, protocols, or ports are not necessary for current business needs, they are disabled or removed as soon as possible and according to change management processes.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Firewall Review Requirements</strong>. Firewall rule sets are reviewed at least every six months.<ul><li>These reviews provide PIPL an opportunity to clean up any unneeded, outdated, or incorrect rules, and ensure that all rule sets allow only authorized services and ports that match current business requirements.</li><li>If appropriate, PIPL reviews occur more frequent than every six months, such as monthly, to ensure that the rule sets are current and match the needs of the business without opening security holes and running unnecessary risks.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Backups</strong>. Periodic backups of firewall configurations and rules will be created and securely stored in a location remote to the device itself. Backups will also be created prior to any rule or configuration change.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p>PIPL builds firewall rule configurations that restrict connections between untrusted networks and internal networks.</p><p><em>Note: An &ldquo;untrusted network&rdquo; is any network that is external to the networks belonging to PIPL, and/or which is out of PIPL&#39;s ability to control or manage. </em></p><p>In order to restrict these connections, PIPL will:</p><ul><li>Restrict inbound and outbound traffic to that which is necessary.<ul><li>This requirement is intended to prevent malicious individuals from accessing PIPL&rsquo;s network via unauthorized IP addresses or from using services, protocols, or ports in an unauthorized manner, such as an intruder sending data to an untrusted server.</li><li>All firewalls will include a rule that denies all inbound and outbound traffic not specifically needed. This will prevent inadvertent holes that would allow other, unintended and potentially harmful traffic in or out.</li><li>Firewall rules will only allow necessary IP protocols through<ul><li>Restricted, whenever possible, to the specific hosts and networks with a need to use them</li></ul></li><li>Firewall rules will only permit appropriate source and destination IP addresses to be used<ul><li>Traffic with invalid source or destination addresses will always be blocked</li><li>Traffic with an invalid source address for incoming traffic or destination address for outgoing traffic (an invalid &ldquo;external&rdquo; address) will be blocked at the network perimeter</li><li>Traffic with a private destination address for incoming traffic or source address for outgoing traffic (an &ldquo;internal&rdquo; address) will be blocked at the network perimeter</li><li>Outbound traffic with invalid source addresses will be blocked</li><li>Incoming traffic with a destination address of the firewall itself will be blocked unless the firewall is offering services for incoming traffic that require direct connections</li></ul></li><li>To provide additional protection, perimeter firewalls will also block:<ul><li>Traffic containing IP source routing information</li><li>Traffic from outside the network containing broadcast addresses that is directed to inside the network</li><li>All incoming traffic to networks and hosts that should not be accessible from external networks</li></ul></li></ul></li><li>To the extent possible all firewall rules will be able to use IPv6, in addition to IPv4, addresses for filtering decisions</li><li>Should sensitive information be accessible over a wireless network, perimeter firewalls will be installed between any wireless networks and the internal network.<ul><li>These firewalls will be configured to deny any traffic from the wireless environment to systems containing sensitive information or to control any such traffic (if such traffic is necessary for business purposes).</li><li>If firewalls do not restrict access from wireless networks to sensitive systems, malicious individuals that gain unauthorized access to the wireless network can easily connect to the systems and potentially compromise PIPL data.</li></ul></li></ul>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:13:"Procedure(s):";s:5:"des_8";s:70:"<p>List any specific configuration or rule change procedures here.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_9";s:105:"<p>Compliance and review are the responsibility of the designated Information Security Officer (ISO).</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:9:"Retention";s:6:"des_10";s:252:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other ORGANIZATION_NAME requirements may stipulate a longer retention.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_11";s:301:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other security policy will result in corrective actions as per the Sanction/Discipline process outlined in the Employee Handbook. Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as HIPAA, HITECH, PCI DSS and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_12";s:76:"<ul><li>Change Control Log</li><li>Firewall Rule Justification Log</li></ul>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_13";s:1938:"<ul><li>PCI DSS Requirements v2.0, PCI Security Standards Council LLC.</li><li>NIST 800-41, Guidelines on Firewalls and Firewall Policies</li><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>HIPAA Final Privacy Rule, 45 CFR Part 164.514(h), Department of Health and Human Services, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/</a> August 14, 2002.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li><em>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</em></li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_14";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";s:11:"subtitle_15";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_15";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_15";s:2:"15";}', '', '', 0),
(1, 1, 'a:42:{s:10:"subtitle_1";s:9:"Policy no";s:5:"des_1";s:13:"<p>ECP-02</p>";s:5:"pos_1";s:1:"1";s:10:"subtitle_2";s:7:"Version";s:5:"des_2";s:11:"<p>14.5</p>";s:5:"pos_2";s:1:"2";s:10:"subtitle_3";s:11:"Approved By";s:5:"des_3";s:17:"<p>Prem Anand</p>";s:5:"pos_3";s:1:"3";s:10:"subtitle_4";s:14:"Effective Date";s:5:"des_4";s:23:"<p>January 16, 2014</p>";s:5:"pos_4";s:1:"4";s:10:"subtitle_5";s:7:"Purpose";s:5:"des_5";s:399:"<p>The purpose is to ensure that Protected Health Information (PHI) transmitted outside of PIPL to other organizations under contract with PIPL is protected and limited to that information needed for providing clinical and administrative services. This policy is intended to act as a guide to transmitting data efficiently while maintaining confidentiality of Protected Health Information (PHI).</p>";s:5:"pos_5";s:1:"5";s:10:"subtitle_6";s:5:"Scope";s:5:"des_6";s:186:"<p>This policy applies to all PIPL workforce members including, but not limited to full-time employees, part-time employees, trainees, volunteers, contractors, and temporary workers.</p>";s:5:"pos_6";s:1:"6";s:10:"subtitle_7";s:6:"Policy";s:5:"des_7";s:1534:"<p>PIPL provides protection on the use and disclosure of PHI transmitted to entities outside of the organization as set forth by the HIPAA Privacy Rule. This includes electronic transmission of health information to external vendors or entities. Individual circumstances dictate the need for specific policies. Refer to the following PIPL policies and procedures for additional information:</p><ol><li>PRIVACY: ECP-03: Minimum Necessary Policy summary: &ldquo;Employees may not use, request, or disclose to others, any PHI that is more than the minimum necessary to accomplish the purpose of the use, request, or disclosure. This includes business information.&rdquo;</li><li>PRIVACY: ECP-06: Use and Disclosure of PHI as Permitted or Required by a Business Associate Agreement (BAA) summary: &ldquo;PIPL and its personnel may use and disclose PHI as permitted or required by a Business Associate Agreement (BAA), and when Client authorization is required to do so.&rdquo;</li><li>SECURITY: ECP-228: Business Associate Agreement and Other Arrangements Policy summary: &ldquo;PHI may be disclosed to a business associate if there is a written agreement with the business associate.&rdquo;</li><li>PRIVACY: ECP-09: Use and Disclosure of PHI Requiring Client Authorization Policy summary: &ldquo;This policy sets forth the circumstances in which PIPL and its personnel must obtain valid Client authorization for a use and disclosure of the Client&rsquo;s PHI. This policy sets the requirements for a valid authorization.&rdquo;</li></ol>";s:5:"pos_7";s:1:"7";s:10:"subtitle_8";s:16:"Responsibilities";s:5:"des_8";s:254:"<p>All individuals identified in the scope of this policy are responsible for meeting the requirements of this policy.<br />The PIPL Privacy Officer is responsible for maintaining this policy and communicating this policy to members of the workforce.</p>";s:5:"pos_8";s:1:"8";s:10:"subtitle_9";s:9:"Retention";s:5:"des_9";s:336:"<p>Every policy and procedure revision/replacement will be maintained for a minimum of six years from the date of its creation or when it was last in effect, whichever is later. Other PIPL requirements may stipulate a longer retention. Log-in audit information and logs relevant to security incidents must be retained for six years.</p>";s:5:"pos_9";s:1:"9";s:11:"subtitle_10";s:10:"Compliance";s:6:"des_10";s:262:"<p>Failure to comply with this or any other privacy policy will result in disciplinary actions as per the Sanction Policy.&nbsp; Legal actions also may be taken for violations of applicable regulations and standards such as the HIPAA Privacy Rule and others.</p>";s:6:"pos_10";s:2:"10";s:11:"subtitle_11";s:7:"Form(s)";s:6:"des_11";s:11:"<p>None</p>";s:6:"pos_11";s:2:"11";s:11:"subtitle_12";s:10:"References";s:6:"des_12";s:1783:"<ul><li>Omnibus HIPAA Final Rulemaking, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/omnibus/index.html</a></li><li>HIPAA Final Privacy Rule, 45 CFR Part 164.514(h), Department of Health and Human Services, <a href="http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/">http://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/privacyrule/</a> August 14, 2002.</li><li>American Reinvestment and Recovery Act of 2009 (ARRA)/(HITECH). <a href="http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf">http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=111_cong_bills&amp;docid=f:h1enr.pdf.</a></li><li>(The HITECH&nbsp;Act begins at&nbsp;H.R. 1-112 through 1-165 (pp. 112 through 165 in the document).&nbsp;The security and privacy provisions are found at Subtitle D &shy; Privacy, beginning H.R. 1-144 (p. 144)).</li><li>Health Information Privacy, Security, and Your EHR</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/ehr-privacy-security</a></li><li>Achieve Meaningful Use: Protect Electronic Health Information</li><li><a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures/protect-electronic-health-information</a> <a href="http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information">http://www.healthit.gov/providers-professionals/achieve-meaningful-use/core-measures-2/protect-electronic-health-information</a></li></ul>";s:6:"pos_12";s:2:"12";s:11:"subtitle_13";s:7:"Contact";s:6:"des_13";s:207:"<p>Maria Vasanth Prem Anand, Information Security Officer<br />6, Manakula Vinayagar St<br />Kailash Nagar, ECR. Lawspet, Puducherry 605008<br />India<br />E: prem.anand@pabrai.com<br />P: 1.800.425.9030</p>";s:6:"pos_13";s:2:"13";s:11:"subtitle_14";s:14:"Policy History";s:6:"des_14";s:47:"<p>Initial effective date: January 15, 2014</p>";s:6:"pos_14";s:2:"14";}', '', '', 0);
